<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Plans for WEU Intervention in Albania: Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Western European Union (WEU) is
not planning a military intervention in Albania to restore order
in the Balkan state, a German government spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"This is a domestic affair ... there are no concrete plans for
a WEU role in stabilizing Albania," said Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
spokesman, Peter Hausmann.
</P>
<P>
With Albania crumbling into anarchy, political leaders in
Tirana appealed late Thursday to the European Union and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to send peacekeeping troops to
the country to help restore order.
</P>
<P>
However, German Foreign Ministry spokesman Martin Erdmann said
Thursday that Bonn did not believe that order could be restored in
Albania by forces from outside. He added that what was happening
there was not a civil war, but "chaos, anarchy, an uprising."
</P>
<P>
The unrests, which started in southern Albania last month and
escalated into armed violence, have spread across the Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
The riots were sparked by the collapse of government investment
schemes which made almost all Albanians lose their life-long
savings.
</P>
<P>
Erdmann said that the new Albanian government, which was formed
on Wednesday, should restore order in the country so that
elections could be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
