<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia for Promoting Gender Equality: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government remains
committed to the promotion of gender equality and the empowerment
of women in national development.
</P>
<P>
This was reiterated by deputy secretary to the cabinet Leslie
Mbula at a gender sensitization seminar for policy analysis and
coordination division here today.
</P>
<P>
Mbula said gender issue should be included in all policies and
laws that will be made in future because if policies that
sideline gender issues continue to be made, women will never be
fully accepted as equal partners with men in development.
</P>
<P>
He noted that gender issues should be given top priority in
all policies because both men and women are capable of making
positive contributions in development.
</P>
<P>
Women in Zambia seem to play no significant role in
development because they are denied access to the country's
resources.
</P>
<P>
They have no access to credit facilities and other productive
materials to enhance productivity, according to Mbula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
