<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela's Envoy to Attend Nairobi Summit on Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela will send a representative to attend a two-day
summit on the the Zairean crisis in Nairobi, Kenya next week,
presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said today.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy of Mandela will soon be named, Mankahlana
said.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi, who is to host the Nairobi summit, has invited Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko, President Paul Biya of Cameroun,
President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, President Pascal Lissouba of
Congo and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa in addition to
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has been at the center of African mediation efforts to
solve the Great Lakes region crisis and held talks with Zairean
rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila last month in Johannesburg,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said Mandela's schedule had been changed to lighten
his workload after a hectic four-nation tour of Southeast Asia
and prior to another to Bangladesh and India from March 26 to 29.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had state visits to the Philippines, Brunei, Singapore
and Malaysia from March 1 to 10, during which business contracts
worth about 1.8 billion U.S. Dollars were signed.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana denied that Mandela's absence should be perceived
as an acknowledgement that South Africa-led mediation efforts had
failed.
</P>
<P>
It is the South African government rather than the president
who is behind the mediation efforts, Mandela's aide said.
</P>
<P>
South African and American officials met Zairean President
Mobutu's envoy and Kabila in Cape Town, the legislative capital
of South Africa, last month in an attempt to broker a cease-fire
and peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
