<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Peace Process Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Mozambican Foreign
Minister Leonardo Simao said today the peace process in his
country is progressing well and that the political situation is
stable.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters here after a meeting with President Robert
Mugabe at Zimbabwe House during which he briefed the Zimbabwean
leader on the current political situation in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Simao said the Mozambique National Assembly is currently
discussing a package of proposals drawn up for municipal
elections scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
''There have been different opinions and views expressed by
the opposition Renamo about the municipal elections and the
proposals, but we hope to reach an agreement and decision soon,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
''However, the overall political situation in Mozambique is
stable and everything is progressing well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Simao expressed gratitude for the support and assistance his
country received from Zimbabwe in dealing with flood victims in
central Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''we had too much rain in December last year and
January this year. We lost 78 lives and as much as 100,000
hectares of crops. They were the most severe floods we have had
in years. We last had such severe floods some 30 to 50 years
back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
