<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The Albanian authorities opened weapons warehouses in the
capital to arm civilians who they hoped would help defend the
government. Residents barricaded themselves inside their homes,
gunfire rattled across the capital, and people bid up the prices
of the last food supplies, awaiting chaos.
</P>
<P>
-- The White House and Congressional Republicans deadlocked
again over the Federal budget. Senate Republican leader Trent Lott
declared President Clinton lacked the courage and leadership to
deal with one of the principal issues, saving billions of dollars
by reducing cost-of-living increases for Social Security and other
benefit programs. Clinton has decided not to look into
recalculating how inflation is measured, which would reduce the
increase.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The House voted largely along party lines Thursday to
approve a compromise measure that would give Mexico 90 days to
make progress toward improving its anti-drug efforts or risk U.S.
sanctions for not cooperating with the United States in the war
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
-- The General Assembly of the United Nations added its voice
Thursday to international criticism of Israel's intention to build
more Jewish homes in East Jerusalem, voting 130 to 2 to condemn
the Israeli plan as "illegal" and "a major obstacle to peace."
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States began evacuating Americans from
Albania. Other countries were taking similar steps as lawlessness
became general, with competing mobs armed with looted army weapons
clashing in the capital and elsewhere. 
</P>
