<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Workers End Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- German construction workers
concluded their weeklong demonstrations in Berlin today with a
mass rally to press their demands on the government.
</P>
<P>
About 15,000 workers from all over the country attended the
final rally at which they called on German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
to take seriously their anger over job losses, cheap imported
labor and broken contracts, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The protests turned violent briefly when a few hundred
demonstrators stormed the Reichstag parliament building
construction site, hurling firecrackers and beer cans. Police said
they had detained one person for vandalism.
</P>
<P>
The protests were staged amid so far fruitless wage
negotiations between the construction workers' union IG Bau and
two employers' groups. The next round of talks was scheduled for
March 25.
</P>
<P>
The employers want a more flexible structure for measuring
annual working hours whereby time lost in the winter months can be
compensated by longer working hours in the summer.
</P>
<P>
While agreeing in principle for a more flexible arrangement,
the union is insisting on "clearly defined maximum and minimum
working time." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
