<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Producer Prices Show Biggest Drop in Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Producer Price Index
(PPI) in February registered the biggest drop in more than two
years, the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the seasonally adjusted 0.4 percent
decrease in the PPI was the sharpest since an identical decline in
October 1994.
</P>
<P>
The PPI measures the cost of goods before they reach consumers.
Its movement offers important clues for the future behavior of the
Consumer Price Index, which tracks the prices of services and
retail goods.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. producer price drop in February followed a 0.3 percent
decline in January.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected decline was another piece of evidence that
sustained robust economic growth hasn't yet translated into
accelerating inflation. Nevertheless, many economists are looking
for the Federal Reserve to nudge interest rates higher as a
preventive measure in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The drop of the PPI resulted from the declines in items ranging
from gasoline to beef and computers, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
February's price decline was helped by a 0.3 percent decrease
in food prices.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices, after a sustained increase in the last half of
1996, fell by 1.2 percent in February, the sharpest drop since
November 1995 and the second consecutive decline.
</P>
<P>
Excluding the volatile food and energy sectors, prices edged
0.1 percent lower after no change the month before. That included
a record 5.2 percent drop in computer prices. Tobacco fell 0.2
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
