<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residency Visa Required for Immigrant Workers' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Children of immigrant workers living
in Germany will be required to have a residency visa under a new
law approved today by the upper house of the German parliament.
</P>
<P>
There are estimately 600,000 to 800,000 children of immigrant
workers from Turkey, Morocco, Tunisia and the former Yugoslavia
now living in Germany. They were previously exempted from
residency permit requirements from the German authorities.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law, those children aged up to 16 will receive
the residency permit automatically if they were born in Germany or
are already registered with state authorities. Otherwise, they are
obliged to apply for the permit.
</P>
<P>
The new law approved today represented a watered-down version
of a decree issued in January by the German Interior Ministry
which demanded even tougher regulations.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people took to the streets across Germany last
month in protest against the planned regulations, with opponents
saying that those regulations would work against efforts to
integrate immigrant workers' children born in the country into the
German society.
</P>
<P>
Defending the new law, Gerhard Glogowski, premier of the Lower
Saxony state, said today that the new visa requirement is useful
because it could protect immigrant workers' children from being
abused by refugee smugglers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
