<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Keeps Door Ajar to Monetary Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 14 (Xinhua)-- A two-year formal linkage to the
Exchange Rate Mechanism (ERM) is not necessary for a country's
currency to qualify for participation in the European Monetary
Union, said Patrick Child, spokesman for the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Child made the remarks to the Swedish newspaper Dagens Industri
before EU finance commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy leaves for
Sweden on a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Sweden, Yves-Thibault is scheduled to meet
with Swedish Finance Minister Erik Asbrink, central bank governor
Urban Backstrom and Peter Wallenberg, the kingpin of Swedish
industry.
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission has previously insisted that linkage to the
ERM be essential for participation in the monetary union. But
Child argued that the stability of a currency was the central
issue.
</P>
<P>
If a two-year membership in the ERM was laid down as a
precondition for joining the monetary union, Sweden would miss out
in the first stage of the monetary union which was set to be
launched in 1999, the Swedish newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
