<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Companies Recommended for Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Union Bank of Switzerland
(UBS), one of the world top banks, showed confidence in Jordan's
economy by identifying eight Jordanian companies as potential
firms for foreign investments, Jordan's news agency Petra reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
The UBS will hold a conference in London on May 15 in an effort
to promote the eight companies among 60 of UBS clients.
</P>
<P>
The eight state-holding companies, in which the government
holds large stakes, are from the industries of phosphate, potash,
cement, electricity and telecommunications as well as the bank and
investment sector, said Amman Financial Market (AFM) Director
General Wahib Shair.
</P>
<P>
A UBS delegation arrived in Amman last Wednesday for a two-day
visit to prepare for the conference, said Shair, adding that the
delegation also met with several Jordanian ministers and officials.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in 1993, Jordan missed many investment
opportunities as foreign investors were required to obtain a prior
approval for investment from the Prime Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"But, with changes in the law brought about by the (Cairo)
Middle East and North Africa economic summit (last November), the
need for prior approval from the Prime Ministry was canceled," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shair stressed the importance of reversing "the traditional
way" of attracting foreign investments, to a new approach
of "meeting investors, showing them we are interested, listening
to their views and communicating their ideas to the government."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
