<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Putting S. Leonean Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today denies having put
visiting Sierra Leoneang rebel leader Foday Sanko under house arrest
in Lagos.
</P>
<P>
A piece of Reuter news, to this effect, could not be confirmed
at this moment, as neither the Nigerian Defense Headquarters nor
the Sierra Leonean High Commission here are available for comment
at this moment.
</P>
<P>
"He's not in detention and he's not a threat to our security,"
a defense spokesman of Nigeria's Defense Headquarters told Xinhua
in a telephone interview. He noted that Sanko is at the federal
government guest house.
</P>
<P>
The same Reuter report also quoted a senior member of Sanko's
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) as saying in a statement today that
the high command of RUF has declared with immediate effect to
sack Sanko as its leader for blocking the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Defense Headquarters on Tuesday confirmed the presence
Sanko in Nigeria for a private visit, but denied holding him for
anything incriminating.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Headquarters also dismissed reports that he came in with
any ammunition as widely reported, adding that he was free to enter
into the country as a West African national.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been in good relations with Sierra Leone. It was only
on last Friday that the two countries recently signed a military
agreement, under which Nigeria will help train Sierra Leone's security
agencies, including that country's Army, Navy, Air Force and Police.
</P>
</TEXT>
