<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Sea Countries Ban "Hoover" Trawlers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Britain's proposal of banning
"industrial" fishing and other damaging trawling methods from
ecologically sensitive areas was adopted at a joint ministerial
conference in Norway, said the newspaper Daily Telegraph here
today.
</P>
<P>
The plan to restrict or prohibit ecologically-damaging fishing
methods took fishermen's representatives by surprise, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
It promises to limit the activities of Danish "hoover" trawlers
that catch sand eels within sight of the salmon rivers and bird
colonies of the British coast.
</P>
<P>
The measure, proposed by John Gummer, the British environment
secretary, represented a major strengthening of the conclusions on
integrating North Sea fisheries and environment policy and saving
endangered fish stocks.
</P>
<P>
The areas regarded as ecologically sensitive now have to be
drawn up by the European Commission, sources attending the
conference said.
</P>
<P>
These are likely to include Wee Bankie, near the Isle of May in
the Firth of Forth, where conservationists believe that the
catching of more than 100,000 tons a year of sand eels has led to
breeding failure in seabird colonies.
</P>
<P>
Anglers, who believe that industrial fishing deprives salmon
and sea trout of food, will take heart from the proposals as will
fishermen who believe that catching small fish is preventing
endangered cod stocks from recovering.
</P>
<P>
But the major fishermen's federations of England and Scotland
were wary of the plans because of the restrictions they could
impose on other forms of fishing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time Is Pressing for PLC, Says Rita Fan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) is facing a heavy workload with only some 100 days
away from the establishment of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) on July 1 this year, PLC President
Rita Fan said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering organized by Xinhua News Agency Hong
Kong Branch, Ms Fan noted that the PLC has no intention of
challenging the governing authority of the British Hong Kong
government, nor will it affect the normal operation of the
existing Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
What the PLC is doing and will do is simply aimed at the smooth
transition of the territory, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Rita Fan summarized the PLC's tasks as "enacting laws and
ordinances indispensable to the establishment of the HKSAR and
handling those (laws and ordinances) that have to be handled
before the first Legislative Council of the HKSAR is formed."
</P>
<P>
Two working groups under the PLC, one on administrative matters
and the other on the rules of procedure, are working hard and
progress has been made, she said.
</P>
<P>
A draft on the rules of procedure will be submitted to the
plenary session of the PLC next Saturday, she said.
</P>
<P>
Once the draft is adopted, she added, the PLC will start with
its legislative work.
</P>
<P>
In the process of making laws, the PLC will employ every
appropriate means to seek opinions of Hong Kong residents, she
continued, hoping that local people would air their views
actively.
</P>
<P>
Around 100 Hong Kong deputies from women and youth
organizations on the Chinese mainland attended the meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
