<HEADLINE> TV Station Collects Consumers' Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A local television station
conducted on-the-spot interviews today to collect complaints from
consumers in the capital city, as part of a series of activities
nationwide to mark the World Consumers' Day.
</P>
<P>
To further raise awareness of consumers' legal rights, the
Diandian Studio of Beijing Television Station organized the
activity at a department store here, offering free consulting
services on consumer rights, services for filing complaints and
free quality checks on goods.
</P>
<P>
This morning alone, the studio received as many as 5,000
visitors and 200 complaints, 68 of which have been channeled to
relevant departments.
</P>
<P>
The visitors accused retailers of selling fake brandnames,
using false advertising, and selling defective goods at a discount.
</P>
<P>
The problem of poor quality accounted for 69 percent of all the
complaints the studio received today. The other top five gripes
deal with weight and measurement errors by vendors, fake goods,
irrational pricing and false advertising.
</P>
<P>
Joining the TV station in the activity were two local
government bodies, the Beijing Industrial and Commercial
Administration and the Bureau of Technical Supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
