<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Appeals For International Help to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat today appealed to international diplomats for help to
rescue the Palestinian-Israeli peace process which is facing deep
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conference of foreign diplomats in Gaza,
Arafat condemned the Israeli government for having put the peace
process on hold with its recent hardline decisions to build a
settlement in East Jerusalem and redeploy troops from only 9
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Envoys from the United States, Russia, Japan, Europan Union
and several Arab countries attended today's meeting, which was
called by Arafat to voice his grievances over the current
situation in an attempt to exert more international pressure on
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel, which has not been invited to this meeting, accused
the conference of violating the peace agreements with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has recently decided unilaterally to
pull out troops from 9 percent of the West Bank in the first of
three-stage pullbacks, which has fallen short of the Palestinian
expectation.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians had expected Israel to return at least 30
percent of the West Bank to Palestinian rule. The Israel offer was
rejected outright by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Israel vowed Friday to carry out its decision to
build the Har Homa neighborhood in southeastern Jerusalem next
week.
</P>
<P>
Accusing Israel of dictating the terms of negotiations, Arafat
said that Israel's recent actions had left the Palestinian side
with no partner in the peace dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"Save the peace process," Arafat repeated three times in his
speech, urging the international community to take actions to
defuse the current crisis and salvage the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also called for establishing an
independent Palestinian state with East Jerusalem as its capital,
a formula that has been flatly ruled out by Israel's hardline
Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Israel has declared Jerusalem as its united, eternal and
indivisible capital.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also called for creating a new mechanism to ensure full
and comprehensive implementation of the peace agreements. But he
did not elaborate what such mechanism would be.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israel's strong opposition, the U.S. sent its
Consul-General in Jerusalem Edward Abington to take part in
today's meeting. This is regarded as Washington' balancing act to
allay the Palestinian frustration over the U.S. veto of the
United Nations Security Council resolution which demanded Israel
abandon the Har Homa project.
</P>
<P>
The real test of the troubled peace process is expected to
come next week as the Israeli cabinet decided Friday to begin the
construction in Har Homa next week.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has repeatedly warned that this could lead to renewed
bloodshed between Israeli troops and Palestinian protesters like
the late September conflicts which killed over 70 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Raise Tobacco Customs Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will impose a 100
percent custom tariffs on tobacco and cigarettes from July 1,
1997, Director General of the Public Administration for Customs
Abdallah Al-Ghanim said today.
</P>
<P>
He was making the announcement at a press conference during a
seminar on coordinated tariff systems among Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states being currently held in Kuwait within the
framework of cooperation between the GCC countries and the
European commission.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently imposes 50 percent of custom tariffs on
imported cigarettes and it is a major consumer country of
cigarettes in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ghanim also said the GCC states including Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain would
soon unify the customs tariffs on some items. The states would
also decide on exempted products and accessories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
