<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalian Launches Silt Cleaning Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a coastal city in
northeastern China's Liaoning Province, today switched on a huge
drainage pump to began sucking out industrial pollution in Dalian
Bay.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, an estimated ten million cubic
meters of industrial waste has silted up over past decades in the
western part of the bay, seriously deteriorating the area. A
300,000-tonnage shipyard adjacent to the water was also affected,
as each new ship had to be thoroughly cleaned before it is put
into use.
</P>
<P>
The local government, working jointly with two local firms,
last year drafted an anti-pollution program to clean the water.
</P>
<P>
The project, due to conclude in July, will pump the industrial
silt and spray to three allocated areas, each with a waste-holding
capacity of one million cubic meters. Construction of a
1,524-meter-long dike designed to hold the waste was completed in
February.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that a new harbor which can accommodate
the stopover of 300,000-tonnage ships could be built after the
project is finished.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
