<HEADLINE> N. Irish Murder Casts New Shadows Over Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Irish republicans today accused
Protestant guerrillas loyal to Britain of killing a Catholic man
on Friday night in his house in Belfast, capital of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The murder, which revived old sectarian fears, cast new shadows
over the province's peace efforts, observers here said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army (IRA), said the victim was a Catholic and blamed
pro-British Protestant guerrillas for his death.
</P>
<P>
"All the indications are at this stage that this was an attack
by a Loyalist death squad. It is additional evidence that confirms
that the Loyalist cessation of violence ended some time ago," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The murder came at a time of heightened tension and a
deteriorating security climate in the province, where rival
factions are in conflict over the future of British rule.
</P>
<P>
One day ago, suspected IRA guerrillas wounded a policeman and a
soldier in the latest Northern Ireland attacks.
</P>
<P>
The IRA is fighting to end British rule and merge Northern
Ireland with largely Catholic Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Loyalist guerrillas have launched four attacks on Catholics
since December, apparently in reprisal for IRA ambushes on British
troops and police. 
</P>
