<HEADLINE> Dalian Shipyard Builds 150,000-Ton Vessel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Dalian New Shipyard, a leading
shipbuilding enterprise in northeast China's Liaoning Province,
today released into water a 150,000-ton oil tanker, a
Chinese-built vessel with the country's largest-ever carrying
capacity.
</P>
<P>
The tanker was built for a Norwegian company, the third of its
kind for the company. In spite of the sluggish shipbuilding
situation overseas, the Dalian shipyard still has stable market
shares in Hong Kong and Norway, and has expanded its business to
Greece and Denmark, shipyard authorities say.
</P>
<P>
Products of the shipyard include 150,000-ton bulk vessels,
150,000- and 110,000-ton oil tankers, and 52,000-ton big-hatch
ships, they said.
</P>
<P>
The shipyard is accepting orders for overseas vessels with
total weight of 1.57 million tons. Construction will continue
through 1999, they said. 
</P>
