<HEADLINE> Shop Declares to Stop Selling Sony TV Sets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A local shop in Haikou, capital
city of South China's Hainan Province, announced beginning from
today -- International Consumers' Day -- that it stops selling all
products manufactured by the Japanese electronics giant Sony.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following a dispute between the shop,
Lepusheng Shopping Building, and Sony's Guangzhou Office, over
whether the Japanese company should replace an allegedly deficient
part for a Sony 2565 color TV.
</P>
<P>
A local consumer named Xu Zhifei discovered the color tube in
his television set wasn't working properly, just two years after
buying it from the shop.
</P>
<P>
Sony's Guangzhou Office refused to replace the bad part free of
charge, thus violating a state-mandated customer service
regulation which states this type of tube should be replaced by
the manufacturer if any quality defect is found within three years
of the date of purchase.
</P>
<P>
The shop has upheld its ban, in spite of a letter of apology
sent by the Sony Office. "Such a letter is not enough to solve the
problem," a Lepusheng source said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
