<HEADLINE> EU Foreign Ministers to Discuss Crisis in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
APELDOORN, the Netherlands, March 15 (Xinhua) -- European Union
foreign ministers are gathering in the Dutch town of Apeldoorn to
hold urgent talks on the crisis in Albania.
</P>
<P>
After days of tension and chaos, the Balkan state were relative
calm in the last few hours. This added to the EU's belief that
military intervention will be "highly inappropriate".
</P>
<P>
As long as the Albanian interim government remains in position,
technically at least, under President Sali Berisha, the EU is
committed to backing their efforts to restore order, an EU
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the call of Organization for Security and Co-operation
in Europe mediator Franz Vranitzky to bring in some sort of
international policing force, the EU foreign ministers do not seem
to share the view, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok, whose country is holding the EU
presidency, has given a cautious response to Vranitzky's call,
saying that there should be a UN mandate for possible
international military intervention.
</P>
<P>
"The UN Security Council should formulate a mandate for the
troops, and the soldiers should know precisely what they are going to
do there," he told a Dutch television on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Danish foreign minister Niels Helveg Petersen, whose
country currently holds the presidency of the OSCE, said on Friday
night that a decision on what to do must be made in the next two
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
