<HEADLINE> Charter Change Advocates Take to Streets in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Constitutional
amendment supporters took to the streets here today to press their
demand for a second term for President Fidel Ramos whose term will
expire in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The paraders were supporters of the People's Initiative for
Reform, Modernization and Action (PIRMA), an organization which
has undertaken a signature-collecting campaign in the past few
months to press for a plebiscite on charter changes.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators carried banners with slogans reading "Let the
People Decide" and "Sign for PIRMA" while marching on a street
leading to the Senate this afternoon. Organizers said earlier that
the marchers will also proceed to the Supreme Court and the
Commission on Elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the local press, at lease one million supporters
of Ramos were to stage nationwide rallies today to counter some
anti-charter change groups which have started rallies in key
cities.
</P>
<P>
The PIRMA failed to submit some six million signatures it
claimed it had collected on March 12 after a water leak in its
office reportedly destroyed some 300,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
Press Secretary Hector Villanueva recently disclosed that
Malacanang (the Presidential Palace) was behind the PIRMA.
However, President Ramos has flatly denied that he would stay in
power beyond 1998.  
</P>
