<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opening-up Is Key to Development for Chongqing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Opening to the outside world is
of major importance for the future development of Chongqing,
China's largest municipality directly under the central
government, and now the largest city in the world, according to
the city's Acting Mayor Pu Haiqing.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua News Agency, Pu said he believes
that Chongqing, as the largest industrial and commercial city in
southwest China, is one of the most ideal spots in the country for
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing has just been separated from Sichuan Province to
become China's fourth municipality, after Beijing, Tianjin, and
Shanghai. The decision is seen as a major move to promote economic
growth in the country's less-developed central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
The new municipality has a population of 30.02 million and
covers an area of over 80,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
As the first Chinese inland foreign trade port city, which
leads the western region in all foreign trade indicators,
Chongqing has laid a solid foundation for opening up to the
outside world, noted 55-year-old Pu.
</P>
<P>
The city has already set up two State-level economic and
hi-tech development zones, which is rare even in large Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
As a heavy industry base, Chongqing boasts strong auto,
machinery, metallurgical, and chemical industries, providing
numerous investment opportunities for large overseas companies.
</P>
<P>
Its favorable location along the banks of the Yangtze River,
China's longest, makes it the the leading water transportation hub
of western China, which also offers convenience to overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing construction of the Three Gorges Project at the
Yangtze is a plus for attracting overseas funds, and will tempt
more overseas financial institutions to open business in
Chongqing, Pu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He believes Chongqing's municipality status plus the
preferential policies enjoyed by the Three Gorges Project will
enable the city to have more autonomy in the opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
"As an investment boom is expected, it is urgently necessary to
further simplify procedures for overseas investors, to set up a
center where overseas business people can file complaints, and to
launch a project data bank, so as to further improve the
investment environment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pu became acting mayor of Chongqing in April, 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Move to Speed up Development of Central, West China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Economists share the view that that Chongqing has the country's
greatest potential for economic growth, Lin said, pointing out
that the city is similar to the large eastern cities in terms of
economic foundation and its degree of openness to the outside
world.
</P>
<P>
And Chongqing will be a springboard for bringing foreign
investment to west China, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Chongqing's special function as a municipality is
closely related to its location: as the largest port on the upper
reaches of the Yangtze River, Chongqing is an important gateway
for the shipment of goods from Sichuan, Yunnan and Guizhou
provinces to the east.
</P>
<P>
In terms of economic strength and structure, Chongqing is the
largest industrial and commercial center in southwest China and is
situated at the rear of the Yangtze Economic Belt, Lin noted.
</P>
<P>
As a municipality, the city will able to use its powerful
administrative authority to adjust industrial structure and
intensify economic cooperation with province-level areas in
southwest China, and to help distribute the abundant natural and
human resources in the southwest, he added.
</P>
<P>
The areas surrounding Chongqing have pinned high hopes on the
city's chance of becoming a municipality. "Through Chongqing, it
will be convenient for us to arrive at the Yangtze River to the
north, and reach Shanghai to the east," said Liu Fangren,
secretary of the Guizhou Provincial Committee of the Chinese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Guizhou started a transportation project to reach the
Yangtze and other waters several years ago. Lu Wanli, director of
the Guizhou Provincial Transportation Department, said that in the
next five years, Chongqing and Guizhou will jointly invest several
 billion yuan in building a super-highway from Chongqing to the
coastal areas in the coastal Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region via
Guiyang, capital of Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Delin, secretary of the Chongqing Municipal Party
Committee, said that the municipality of Chongqing will promote
the urbanization process and better serve the resettlement of over
one million people for the construction of the Three Gorges
Project on the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
"The 30 million people of Chongqing now have taken up a
glorious and arduous task," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Move to Speed up Development of Central, West China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The upgrading of Chongqing's
status from a city in Sichuan Province to a municipality directly
under the central government is a significant move to speed up the
development of the country's central and western areas, economics
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
"The upgrading of Chongqing's status is not a result of the
city's need to seek greater administrative authority along with
its increased economic strength," senior economist Lin Ling
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
"It is a result of the country's need to readjust the country's
economic structure, to achieve the sustained, stable and healthy
development of the national economy, and to coordinate the
development of east and west China," said Lin, director-general of
the China Comprehensive Development Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing became China's fourth municipality, following formal
approval by the just-concluded Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress. The other three municipalities are
Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The central and west areas, which include 18 provinces and
autonomous regions, account for 86 percent of the China's
territory and 58 percent of the country's population. Historical
legacies and restrictive natural conditions have caused the
economic development of central and west China to lag behind the
coastal areas in the east.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the widening gap between the east and west in
economic growth has attracted widespread attention; some of the
wealthiest areas in the country are located along the lower
reaches of the Yangtze River, while the country's largest
poverty-stricken region can be found along the upper reaches,
where nearly 20 million people live below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
The gap between the most developed area and the most
underdeveloped area along Yangtze in terms of the per-capita GDP
has widened from 2:1 in 1990 to 4:1.
</P>
<P>
The disproportionate economic growth of the upper and lower
reaches of the Yangtze is most illustrative of the imbalanced
development of west, central and east China, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
