<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Set Language Benchmarks for Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong plans to establish
language-teaching standards for teachers in a bid to improve
language teaching quality.
</P>
<P>
New teachers will have to meet benchmark standards in English,
Cantonese and putonghua from 1999 before being allowed to take up
employment, today's South China Morning Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile more than 20,000 teachers, mainly in primary and
junior secondary schools, will also be tested.
</P>
<P>
Those who fail to reach the benchmark could lose their jobs,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Wong Wing-ping, secretary for education and manpower, said the
Hong Kong government plans to spend 15 million HK dollars (1.92
million U.S. dollars) in the new financial year on a pilot
exercise to establish language-teaching standards.
</P>
<P>
"The exercise is one of the initiatives taken by the government
to enhance the language standards and professionalism of teachers
and, in turn, the quality of teaching and learning in schools," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Teachers will be tested on their writing, reading, listening
and oral skills. Language performance in the classroom will also
be assessed, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
