<HEADLINE> EU Gives Loans of 33m Dollars to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government and the
European Union (EU) have signed here a contract for a
concessionary loan of 33 million U.S. Dollars to be injected in
the private sector development.
</P>
<P>
According to The New Vision daily today, this is the second
tranche in a series of loans given to Uganda under the
arrangement code-named Uganda Apex Private Enterprises ii. The
first lump of money under the same program amounted to 20 million
Dollars and has been utilized exhaustively.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Minister for Finance (privatization) Matthew Rukikaire
and David White from the European Investment Bank inked the
contract for their respective government and organization.
</P>
<P>
Rukikaire said small and medium scale entrepreneurs engaged in
agro-industry, tourism and horticulture will optimally utilize
the 33 million Dollars fund released to Uganda by the EU.
</P>
<P>
White said that this kind of investment was aimed at fostering
export capacity, developing competitive business activity and
enhancing local investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
