<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Government Urges SMEs to Upgrade Themselves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government today
urged the Small and Medium-sized Enterprises (SMEs) of the country
to do more to upgrade themselves to take advantage of the economic
opportunities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a function of the Singapore Chinese Chamber of
Commerce and Industry (SCCCI), Trade and Industry Minister Lee
Yock Suan said that the government will continue to help the SMEs,
but they must also do their part to venture out.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the SMEs take part in overseas trade
delegations, access new information networks, and make use of the
government's assistance schemes.
</P>
<P>
To stay competitive, the SMEs must also improve their
management methods and tighten their cost control to meet the
demands of shorter product life cycles.
</P>
<P>
In the retail sector, which had been struggling with continued
sluggishness of the market, the minister said, the SMEs need to
seek new product lines or diversify into new businesses.
</P>
<P>
Some of the potential fields for the SMEs in the retail sector
were property, tourism, trade and industrial areas like
electronics, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
