<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Go out to Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Quite a lot of Nigerians today
have gone out of their houses to vote in the local government
council elections on party basis, a major step under the military
government's transition to civil rule.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, Nigeria's largest city and commercial center, the
situation is calm and orderly. As the government has imposed a
traffic restriction, there are few vehicles except those of
patrolling police and election officials.
</P>
<P>
At a polling station on the Victoria Island, voters have kept
coming since 8:00 in the morning, when the polling started
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
By the time of the press, the presiding election official said
some 300 people have cast their ballots. About 800 voters are
registered at the station and are expected to come by 4:00 in the
afternoon, when the polling will end.
</P>
<P>
Voters produce their registration cards to the officials at
the station. They are then given two ballots, one for local
government councillors and one for chairmen.
</P>
<P>
On each ballot are the names of the five political parties
contesting for the elections. The voters thumbprint the party of
their choice on the ballots and drop them into the ballot boxes
of the National Electoral Commission of Nigeria (NECON).
</P>
<P>
A councillor contestant of the Democratic Party of Nigeria
said his party has a high chance to win both in the Lagos State
and nationwide.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence in the ongoing elections, saying
that unlike the aborted elections in 1993, none of the political
parties this time are government parties.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, there are some 56 million people, or slightly more
than half of the whole population that are registered as voters,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
The figure is quite high as official census says about 45
percent of the population are children under 15 and three percent
elders above 64.
</P>
<P>
A young man who came to the polling station for a look said he
was not registered because he is busy in finding a job. Besides,
he said, he does not know who is who of those parties.
</P>
<P>
The result of the elections is expected to be known later
today, according to election officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Marks World Consumers' Rights Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Macao today staged a contest of
dramas among nine middle schools in a bid to enhance the awareness
 of students and local residents on protecting the legitimate
rights of consumers.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of the activities to mark the "March 15 --
World Consumers' Rights Day" in Macao, said a spokesman for the
Macao Consumers' Commission, a non-governmental organization.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that his commission stages various kinds
of events every year to increase consumers' awareness of the
importance of protecting their own rights.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the commission has suggested that the authorities
make laws on the safety of products and establish a "consumers'
voluntary arbitration center."
</P>
<P>
Disputes concerning consumers' rights were rarely reported in
the territory. But the commission did warn consumers sometimes of
possible danger of some products.
</P>
<P>
The Macao government has also stepped up protection of the
rights of tourists. In a latest move, the Government Tourism
Office has established a "Tourist Aid Center", which accepts
complaints from tourists during their stay in Macao. So far, it
has helped the rebate of over 1.16 million patacas (about 146,800
US dollars) from shop owners who cheated tourists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Gears Up for New Film Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is gearing up for the
launch of its first-ever film market in June this year, according
to the Trade Development Council today.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC),
Filmart '97, which is to run from June 11 to 13 at the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center, will provide a full range of
Hong Kong and Asian products for prospective buyers from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
Jenny Koo, TDC's manager of services promotion, said that the
Filmart '97 is to promote Hong Kong and Chinese language films and
consolidate the territory's position as a regional hub for those
seeking to do business in Asia and China.
</P>
<P>
According to Koo, the Chinese Ministry of Radio, Film and
Television will attend the fair by displaying the largest range
of features, TV programs and documentaries ever to be promoted
outside of the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong exhibitors confirmed at the fair will include Golden
Harvest, Media Asia Films, and Mandarin Films, she said.
</P>
<P>
TDC's Assistant Executive Director, Alan Wong said that Hong
Kong is the world's second largest film exporter and the third
largest film producer, after the United States and India.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we believe that the export of Hong Kong's film
industry can expand further, due to increased demand from
satellite and cable television and new home entertainment
technology."  
</P>
</TEXT>
