<HEADLINE> NPC Session Hailed in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's newspapers today
devoted pages to reporting the Fifth Session of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) which closed in Beijing Friday.
</P>
<P>
The NPC meeting, which passed two laws, eight resolutions and
three legal decisions, was described by many local newspapers as
very "successful and fruitful".
</P>
<P>
An editorial carried on today's Ta Kung Pao said the session
was very "democratic and practical".
</P>
<P>
It said the conference paid great attention to Hong Kong's
smooth transition, prosperity and stability. The Draft on how to
elect deputies from the HKSAR to the Ninth NPC and the HKSAR
Preparatory Committee Work Report were both passed with strong
support from NPC members, which showed that the efforts to form
the HKSAR government have been highly praised and fully
acknowledged by the whole people.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Commercial Daily said that since China initiated
its opening and reform policy, great progress has been scored in
the introduction of a complete legal system. In the past year
alone, the NPC has passed over 20 laws and regulations, and many
more are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
"There is still much work to do for China to institute a united
and complete legal system, but the fundamental laws have been
gradually completed, and laws concerning certain areas have
already been framed," the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po used pages of pictures and reports to brief
Chongqing City to Hong Kong people. Chongqing, previously
governed by Sichuan province, won approval Friday from the NPC to
become China's fourth municipality directly under the central
government.
</P>
<P>
One of its reports said this is a wise decision and that the
new status would enable Chongqing to accelerate the development in
China's central west regions, and to speed up the undertaking of
the great Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
Most Hong Kong newspapers agreed that the session showed the
Chinese leadership headed by Jiang Zemin will continue to abide by
the policies of late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the view that China will surely be able to
maintain its economic growth momentum and that its overall
situation will become even better. 
</P>
</TEXT>
