<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Thousands of Albanians are trying to embark on boats often
by force at Durres, a port city 40 kilometers west of Tirana, to
flee their own country -- where they said "there is no more
future" -- to neighboring Italy, the land which is paved with gold
in the eyes of Albanians. Meanwhile, the Italian government has
reiterated that it would not accept Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
-- The European Union and the United States are worried about
the possible extension of violence in Albania to other Balkan
states.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is close to an agreement to send an
international police force to Albania, a position suggested by
former Austrian chancellor Frank Vranitzky and supported by the
Netherlands and Denmark, which are the current chairmen of the
European Union and the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe respectively, as well as Italy and Greece.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- France's political class has strongly reacted to the
discovery by police of a paedophile network existing in the
country, in which dozens of people from all social classes are
involved.
</P>
<P>
Eric Dolige, a deputy of the ruling RPR party in the French
National Assembly has called for the establishment of a
parliamentary investigation commission to "propose a more
effective way of protecting children" while the Minister of
National Education Francois Bayrou has suspended the jobs of some
school teachers suspected of paedophilia.
</P>
<P>
-- In the streets of Tirana today, there is no law except that
of the strongest. After weapon storehouses were looted, the
streets are owned by young wolves armed with Kalachnikov assault
guns whose only desire is to loot and racketeer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
