<HEADLINE> Chinese Navy Commander Meets Malaysian Counterpart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUMUT, Malaysia, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Vice Admiral
Yang Yushu, commander of East China Sea Fleet of the Chinese PLA
Navy, met here today with Rear Admiral Mohd Hussain Bin Tamby,
fleet operations commander of the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN).
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, both stressed the need for promoting mutual
understanding and strengthening friendship between the two navies
through exchange of visits to make contributions to the
development of friendship between the armed forces of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Hussain told the Chinese commander that "you have not only
brought in beautiful naval ships, but also brought in the deep
friendship of the Chinese people to Malaysia."
</P>
<P>
Yang Yushu said that with the further development of relations
between China and Malaysia, the friendship between the two armed
forces is also strengthening.
</P>
<P>
"We are here as peace promoters and I believe that the exchange
of visits is conducive to further cementing the relationship
between our two navies and will write a new page in the history of
contacts between our two navies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two commanders also briefed each other on the general facts
of the respective navy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese commander came here earlier today at the invitation
of the RMN with two Chinese naval ships -- missile destroyer
"Qingdao" and missile frigate "Tongling" -- which called at the
Lumut port for a three-day friendly visit to Malaysia. This is the
first visit of Chinese naval ships to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Lumut, located in Malaysia's northwest state of Perak, about
288 kilometers from Kuala Lumpur, is the largest navy base in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Malaysia, Commander Yang Yushu is also
scheduled to meet RMN Chief Ahmad Ramli Mohamed Noor while the
Chinese sailors will have friendly football and basketball
matches with their Malaysian counterparts.  
</P>
