<HEADLINE> Army Command in N. Uganda Has Minor Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The army command in northern
Uganda has had a ''minor change''in a bid to cope with the rebels
there better, The New Vision paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Army sources in the fourth division in the north were quoted
as saying the aim of the reorganization is to uproot the
rebellion in the north.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Shaban Bantariza, the public relation officer of the
fourth division, confirmed that Col. James Kazini, the commander
of the fourth division, ''has been away for some days now from
his Gulu office on duties''.
</P>
<P>
Many other officers have joined the combing operations in the
areas suspected to be the hideouts of the rebels, and many rebels
have either been killed or were forced to surrender to the
Ugandan army in the operations, the newspaper added.
</P>
<P>
The change in the army command in the north also involved
Major General Salim Saleh, the most high-ranking officer in the
north who was moved from Gulu to Arua. He is the senior
presidential adviser on military and political affairs in the
north.
</P>
<P>
The main forces in the north is the fourth division whose
headquarters are in the northern city of Gulu. Arua is the city
where the operation command in the West Nile under the fourth
division is situated.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Salim Saleh was transferred there to
eradicate West Nile Bank Front (WNBF) rebels.
</P>
<P>
There are two Sudan-backed rebel groups acting in northern
Uganda: WNBF and the Lord's Resistance Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
Yoweri Moseveni, the President of Uganda and the
Commander-in-Chief of Uganda Armed Forces, now is in northern
Uganda to oversee army operations against the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
