<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Asian Economic Growth Expected to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- After up and down years, the Asian
economic growth is expected to stabilize this year though the
current export performance has showed no sign of a quick recovery.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the economic growth of the developing Asia slowed down
its pace after export in the region was hard hit by cyclical
downturns in electronics. From 8.3 percent in 1994, the growth
rate declined to 7.9 percent in 1995 and 7.3 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The marginal decline in the growth rate is also due partly to
steps taken by governments like China and Malaysia to prevent
overheating of their economies.
</P>
<P>
However, Asia's growth rate last year was still at least twice
as high as those in the West.
</P>
<P>
"I think '94 and '95 were kind of excessive years and '96 was a
period of adjustment; '97 should be a much stable year," said Neil
Saker, senior regional economist at Crosby Securities Pte. Ltd..
</P>
<P>
A recovery in exports and increased foreign investment should
see the economy emerge from its "adjustment period" and continue
to grow at an average of 7.3 percent to 7.8 percent in 1997,
economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank predicted last November that the
export growth slide will give way to a recovery by the first
quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the current export performance in the region is proving a
slow slog, and in some countries drops in exports have been
reported since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's trade deficit widened to 3.48 billion U.S.
dollars in January from a shortfall of 2.13 billion a year earlier
due to the country's sharp drop in exports of semi-conductors.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports of semi-conductors fell 44 percent
year-to-year in the month, to 1.22 billion dollars, affected by
weak prices on international markets.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, non-oil domestic exports in January dropped 3.1
percent to 5.16 billion dollars from a year earlier. The weak
performance of the electronics sector was underlined by a 8.3
percent drop in exports of semi-conductor components compared with
the corresponding period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
But economists remain optimistic about the recovery, because
indicators such as the U.S. semi-conductor book-to-bill ratio and
industrial growth rate in member countries of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development suggested the export growth
will speed up in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
They generally agree that last year's poor export performance
was largely cyclical and not structural in nature, that is why a
rebound is widely anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Yet they stressed that any recovery in exports will be uneven
-- China's rebound is evident while some of its neighbors,
including Thailand and South Korea, will remain in the doldrums,
and may not become fully apparent until the second quarter of the
year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the expected upturn in exports, analysts cited
lower inflation in Asian countries as good signs of stable growth.
In most Asian economies, there are few alarm bells sounding over
inflation now, economists said.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, the inflation rate is projected at 4.7 percent
this year, 0.2 percent higher than last year's figure. Analysts
surveyed by research institutions expect China's consumer price
inflation to rise slightly from 8.3 percent last year to 9.1
percent in 1997 thanks to higher utility and commodity prices.
That is far better than the double-digit levels of a few years
back, they said.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, inflation in February rose only 4.4 percent
from the same month of 1996, and the date is making the
government's target of 6-7 percent inflation for the year "more
achievable."
</P>
<P>
Another good sign for stable growth is the decline of the
Japanese yen against other Asian currencies, because it will
reduce deficit in the current account, a broad measure of trade in
goods and services. The weaker yen helped lower the cost of the
flood of Japanese machines and components that are imported by
manufacturers across the region.
</P>
<P>
As large deficits are often a sign of overheated economies, the
reduction in deficits would attract more foreign investors and
mean stable growth, economists said.
</P>
<P>
If the favorable trends continue to develop, the Asian economy
will achieve steady and smooth growth this year, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors to Give Big Sum for Ethiopia's Social </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Bilateral and multilateral
donors have agreed to give 655 million U.S. Dollars to projects
in Ethiopia's sectors of health and education, resident
representative of the World Bank here Fayez Omar has said.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald reported today that the representative
made the announcement Friday at the end of a three-day workshop
organized by the government on Ethiopia's social sector
investment programs and indicative budgetary support of donors at
Debre Zeit, 40 kms east of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
Omar said out of the 655 million Dollars, 323 million was
meant for the health sector which was the very amount the sector
needed.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the sum of 332 million for the
education sector accounts for just 70 percent of the expected
amount and that it was short by a hefty 148 million Dollars,
elevating the total required funds to not less than 480 million
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
But, he said that there is a room for optimism as there are
many donors, who did not participate in the workshop and hence
could not propose their pledges and that this gap in the
financing of the education sector could be filled when they show
up with their pledges.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the report, the World Bank has pledged
to allocate 340 million Dollars at the workshop, out of which 150
million Dollars will be disbursed for the health and the
remaining 190 million Dollars for the education sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
