<HEADLINE> Zairean Rebel Leader Meets UN Envoy in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader Laurent
Kabila refused to effect a cease-fire while meeting the U. N.
special envoy to the Great Lakes region Mohammed Sahnoun in
Uganda's northern town of Gulu on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mass media here reported today that Kabila entered Uganda
through Entebbe airport, 40 km south of here on Wednesday and was
immediately flown to Gulu town where he met the Ugandan President
Y. Museveni before meeting Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
Kabila reportedly rejected pleas y Sahnoun for a cease-fire
in the five month offensive against Zairean President Mobutu Sese
Seko, saying it could only be considered if Mobutu declared his
willingness to hold direct talks with the Democratic Forces of
Alliance for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) led by him.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela last month failed to
broker direct talks between Mobutu's envoy and Kabila and a mini
African summit will be held in Nairobi on March 19 in a bid to
solve the Zaire crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tusis-led ADFL rebel forces took up arms to fight Mobutu last
October and they are marching toward Kisangani, the third largest
city in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, a regional power broker, accused by Zaire of backing
Kabila who facilitated the face to face meeting, has refused to
take sides, diplomats here were quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
