<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- At least seven people were killed and about 15
injured in a bomb blast in Pakistan's eastern Punjab Province, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bomb went off at 1:05 p.m. (0735 GMT) Friday in a car park
outside the main railway station in the eastern Punjab city of
Jullundhar, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Police said there were heavy casualties because the station was
crowded at that time. The Punjab police have blamed a militant
group for the blast.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The gunfire which has echoed around the capital
Tirana was muted Friday evening after police and military
reinforcements appeared on the streets and a dusk to dawn curfew
was imposed.
</P>
<P>
About four to five armored vehicles carrying heavily-armed men
patrolled the main streets of the city, checking private cars,
especially those without license plates.
</P>
<P>
The usual crowds of shoppers have disappeared as shops in the
capital have all closed. Only a few people were out, running up
and down the main streets, giving out leaflets to journalists and
anyone else they could find.
</P>
<P>
Some of the leaflets read, "We should unite in the hard times.
Our children should not be without a motherland."
</P>
<P>
An emergency curfew has been imposed, forbidding people to go
out onto the streets from 19:00 to 07:00.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton said he will go to
Helsinki as planned for a summit with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin next week in spite of undergoing surgery for a torn knee
tendon Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was speaking to reporters after a successful two-hour
operation to repair the tendon at the Bethesda Naval Hospital in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
The president tore the tendon in his right knee after slipping
on the stairs at the Florida home of Australian golfer Greg Norman
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Friday that his
summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton next week would be the
hardest talks since he became Russian president in 1991 and the
"hardest in the history of Russian-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin did not exclude the possibility of a fruitless ending
to the talks, saying that "we will not make any compromise that
may weaken Russia's defense ability."
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia will never agree to let Americans deploy
conventional weapons on the territories of eastern European
countries, formerly members of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
