<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Govt Plans to Wipe Out Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government is planning to launch an extensive campaign to wipe
out smuggling in a bid to improve trade revenue collection.
</P>
<P>
A local daily The Citizen today quoted Deputy Finance Minister
Gill Marcus as saying that the restructuring of the customs and
excise department was possibly the government's toughest
challenge in the reformation of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a budget workshop in Midrand, north of
Johannesburg, Marcus said measures, among others, targeted to
stop smuggling of goods in and out of the country included
slashing the number of international airports and restructuring
border posts.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the government had to regain control of
traffic through the country's border posts and eliminate the lack
of control at the numerous international airports, she said.
</P>
<P>
Marcus said the number of international airports would be cut
from 36 at preset to about eight, while the border posts would be
reduced from 118 to 16.
</P>
<P>
In his Budget speech on Wednesday, Finance Minister Trevor
Manuel said high tariffs had led to a greater incentive for tax
evasion by way of illicit trade.
</P>
<P>
Manuel announced a 20 percent tariffs cut on a range of goods,
including video recording and audio equipment, motorcycles,
beauty and hair care preparations, clothing and furs, spectacles
and watches.
</P>
<P>
He said, however, the revenue loss resulted from tariffs cut
would be partially offset by improved collections because of a
reduction in smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
