<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Sweep World Cup Freestyle Aerial Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Canadiens Nicholas Fontaine and
Veronica Brenner won the World Cup Freestyle aerial overall titles
in Hundfjallet, Sweden Friday.
</P>
<P>
Fontaine was fourth in the men's final event, which was won by
Christian Rivajec of Austria with 241.23 points. Fontaine, who
won the world championships in Nagano, Japan, last month, had
230.50 points. David Belhumeur of Canada was runner-up with 234.39
and Eric Bergoust of the United States third with 231.39.
</P>
<P>
Fontaine topped the overall standing with 824 points, well
ahead of Frenchman Jean-Damien Climonet, who had 784 points.
Climonet was seventh in Friday's run with 192.15 points.
</P>
<P>
Andy Capicik of Canada was third in the overall standing with
728 points, followed by Belhumeur with 704 and Jeff Bean of the
United States with 612.
</P>
<P>
Kirstie Marshall of Australia won the women's event with 168.61
points, ahead of former world champion Nikki Stone, of the United
States, with 165.87 and Brenner, bronze medallist in the World
Championships, with 155.84.
</P>
<P>
The win was enough for Marshall, the ruling world champion, to
move into second spot of the final standings with 728 points, 48
points behind Brenner.
</P>
<P>
Caroline Olivier of Canada was third with 708 points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
