<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Ships Call at Lumut Base in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUMUT, Malaysia, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese naval ships
under the command of Vice Admiral Yang Yushu, Commander of East
China Sea Fleet of the Chinese PLA Navy arrived at the Lumut port
here today for a three-day friendly visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Lumut, located in Malaysia's northwest state of Perak, about
288 kilometers from Kuala Lumpur, is the largest navy base in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival, commander Yang Yushu said in a written
statement that "This is the first visit of Chinese naval ships to
Malaysia. We come for friendship, we come for promoting mutual
understanding and exchanges, and we come for strengthening the
friendly relations between the two armed forces and especially
between the two navies."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that this visit would surely further
enhance the continuous development of the friendly relations
between the two peoples, two armed forces and two navies of China
and Malaysia and write a new page in the history of contacts
between the two navies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese naval ships were welcomed at the berth 4 of the
base by Assistant Chief of Staff of the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN)
and other senior RMN officers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ships came in after visiting Sattahip, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the visit in Malaysia, Commander Yang Yushu and
Commanding officers of the two ships -- Missile Destroyer Qingdao
and Missile Frigate Tongling -- will meet the Malaysian fleet
operations commander, Rear Admiral Mohd Hussain Bin Tamby, and the
Royal Malaysian Navy chief, Ahmad Ramli Mohamed Noor. The Chinese
sailors will have friendly football and basketball matches with
their Malaysian counterparts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
