<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urged to Reform Rural Financing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank, one of the largest
donors to Bangladesh, has underlined in a study the importance of
carrying out reforms in the country's rural financing in order to
achieve the desired growth of the economy.
</P>
<P>
With the reform, the bank hoped, financial services would be
available to poor sections of the rural population who currently
have no access to such service, especially small and marginal
farmers and entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The future of Bangladesh's economy, which is still rural based,
lies in the development of farming and farm-related activities,
said the study published here today.
</P>
<P>
The reform in rural financing is necessary since the current
operating environment "threatens to constrain further
development," said the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Three types of lending institutions now exist in Bangladesh:
public-sector institutions (agriculture banks and nationalized
commercial banks), member-based institutions like Grameen Bank and
 informal financial intermediaries like money lenders, traders and
dealers.
</P>
<P>
The rural financial market is fragmented, inefficient and
inadequate, said the World Bank, which suggested that policy and
institutional reforms should be carried out soon.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that when efficient and cost-effective financial
services are made available, Bangladesh will have created an
environment for entrepreneurship, innovation and production of the
rural population, thereby helping the growth of the entire
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soil Erosion in Indonesia Causes Heavy Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is losing 315 million
U.S. dollars each year as a result of soil erosion in river basins
in Java, an expert said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a workshop on a system to monitor changes in the
soil of East Java's Brantas River held Friday in Malang, East
Java, Cahyaningtas, expert of the Indonesian Institute of
Sciences, said soil erosion is one of the impacts of an imbalanced
hydrological system.
</P>
<P>
The imbalanced hydrological system has also led to
sedimentation, reports reaching here today quoted the expert as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The loss caused by sedimentation reached an average of 91
million dollars a year, she said.
</P>
<P>
The erosion and sedimentation would worsen the surface water
supply situation in Java, where more than 60 percent of the
Indonesians are living, she added.
</P>
<P>
Demand for surface water in Java reached 721 million cubic
meters in 1990 and will increase to 998 million cubic meters in
1997, she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
