<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thailand Faces Shortage of Doctors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Lack of medical workers,
especially doctors, is one of the problems facing skilled
labor-thirsty Thailand today after its economic success and the
government is taking measures to correct the situation.
</P>
<P>
Thailand currently has about 13,400 doctors practicing
nationwide, but it needs at least 15,000 more to take care of its
60 million population, in particular in the rural areas, according
to the Thai Public Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The most serious situation is seen in the country's remote
northeastern region, where one doctor has to serve 10,740 people.
</P>
<P>
Bangkokians are lucky to have the highest doctor-population
ratio of 1 to 909 in the country, as nearly half of the country's
doctors are working in the capital for better medical facilities
and good salaries.
</P>
<P>
The draining of doctors from the public sector to the private
sector, or from rural areas to cities, further undermines the
country's public health care.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only about 6,400 doctors work at hospitals under the
Public Health Ministry. Many doctors or medical students go to
private hospitals for better earnings or to government health
administrative agencies.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the doctor shortage, the Chavalit government
recently set up a special national commission, together with the
introduction of incentives and compulsory measures to retain
doctors.
</P>
<P>
At its first meeting chaired by Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh on Friday, the commission approved significant
increases in wages for doctors working in hospitals' high-risk
areas, ranging from 2,700 to 20,000 baht (108 to 800 U.S. dollars)
per month, to boost their morale.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Public Health Ministry is considering hiking
salaries to 4 million or 5 million baht (160,000 or 200,000
dollars) for those doctors who received their education under
government scholarships and want to quit working in the government
hospitals before completing their term.
</P>
<P>
Doctors who do not complete a three-year term in government-run
hospitals currently are liable to a fine of 400,000 baht (16,000
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Athasit Vejjajiva, rector of Thailand's well-known Mahidol
University, also suggested that the Public Health Ministry should
encourage more doctors to work at hospitals while employing
administrative officials from other sectors like the economic
sector.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Thai government is urging public and private
universities to bring up more medical students each year to help
ease the country's doctor shortage.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 12 government universities and one private
university produce 850 to 900 doctors each year. The Thai Public
Health and University Affairs Ministries have worked out two
special programs to produce 640 more each year.
</P>
<P>
The government is also considering attracting Thai doctors
working aboard to return to Thailand but requiring them to undergo
additional training.
</P>
<P>
On the average, one doctor now has to take care of about 4,300
people in Thailand. Thai health officials said it would take at
least 20 years for their country to get enough doctors, or one
doctor for every 1,800 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
