<HEADLINE> Nepali Government to Seek Confidence Vote Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali coalition
government, which took office last Wednesday, will seek a vote of
confidence in the parliament before March 23, the official news
agency RSS today quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Supplies Minister Gajendra Narayan Singh said Friday in a
southern Nepali town that the present eight-member cabinet led by
Lokendra Bahadur Chand will be expanded after the government wins
the confidence vote in the lower house.
</P>
<P>
Singh, also president of the Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP), a
ruling partner of the newly-formed coalition led by Chand's
National Democratic Party (RPP), said the three-party government
will make its policies and programs public soon.
</P>
<P>
Another partner of the ruling coalition is the Communist Party
of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), the largest party in
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Chand's RPP and Singh's NSP were ruling partners of the former
three-party government led by Sher Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali
Congress (NC) party, which resigned last week after losing a
confidence vote in the house partly due to the two ruling
partners' withdrawal from the coalition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
