<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmenistan Not Uneasy Over NATO Enlargement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkmenistan's President
Saparmurad Niyazov said today he did not feel uneasy over the
enlargement plans of the NATO military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan, a former central Asian Soviet republic and now a
member of the Commonwealth Independent States (CIS), understood
the changes taking place in NATO and its role in peace keeping,
Niyazov said during a meeting with visiting NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO did not intend to replace the security system
already put in place by the CIS in the region, Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides agreed that Russia's stand and
participation are a decisive factor in NATO's eastward expansion
and the establishment of a future security system.
</P>
<P>
Noting Solana's recent tour of a series of former Soviet
countries, Russian President Boris Yeltsin warned on Friday that
NATO should not try to draw in any of the 12 states in the CIS or
the three Baltic states of Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who is expected to return to Brussels tonight, also met
with Foreign Minister Boris Shikhmuradov and Defense Minister
Danatar Kopekov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
