<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Foreign Exchange Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The foreign exchange assets of
the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) are estimated to have surged by a
massive 600 million U.S. dollars during the past seven days to
reach 20.6 billion dollars on Friday, RBI sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The surge witnessed last week is 200 million more than the 400
million mopped up by the RBI in the week after the union budget
tabled before the parliament on February 28.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the figure is expected to go up further on account
of the increased inflows of foreign institutional investors (FII)
as well as the continuous RBI buying in the foreign exchange
market.
</P>
<P>
RBI Governor C. Rangarajan has indicated that the central bank
would continue to intervene in the foreign exchange market to mop
up U.S. dollars in order to stop the rupee from appreciating
further.
</P>
<P>
The net FII inflows totaled 98.6 million dollars in the first
11 days of this month. The total investment inflow since the
beginning of the current calendar year is 276.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The inflow of foreign direct investment in 1996 was 2.4 billion
dollars, 300 million more than the inflow in 1995, but 1.6 billion
less than the United Front government's target for the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
