<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yantai to Enhance Foreign Trade, Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANTAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Yantai, a coastal city of east
China's Shandong Province, will work to achieve a foreign trade
volume of three billion US dollars this year, a rise of 20 percent
over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Information from the city's committee of foreign trade and
economic cooperation shows that the city also hopes to have a
promised inflow of one billion US dollars in foreign funds in 1997.
</P>
<P>
To fulfil the goal, Yantai will give priority to the
development of the processing industry by making full use of its
geographical advantages of being near the Republic of Korea (ROK)
and Japan and its rich labor resources.
</P>
<P>
The city will cooperate closely with big commercial firms and
try hard to attract overseas investors to high-tech and
capital-intensive projects and old enterprises, and encourage them
to participate in the city's major construction projects and in
technical upgrading of state-owned large and medium-sized
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city will advance the use of overseas
funds in the service trade, especially retail, circulation, and
financial sectors, and encourage overseas investors to help
develop export-oriented agriculture and build infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The city will concentrate efforts on building five bases of
metallurgy, chemicals, building materials, gold mining, meters and
time pieces, and on vigorously developing sectors involving the
production of automobiles, machinery, electronics, chemical fibers
and textiles, foodstuffs and pharmaceuticals, and polyurethane.
</P>
<P>
Yantai, also a seaside summer resort, will advance economic
and technological cooperation and exchanges with Japan, ROK,
Southeast Asian countries, and Hong Kong, and Taiwan, and keep
opening new overseas markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
