<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangpu Development Zone Sees Large Investment Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Yangpu Economic Development
Zone in south China's Hainan Province has become a base for large
investment projects.
</P>
<P>
On March 7, China National Offshore Oil Corporation (CNOOC)
announced that it will invest 5.5 billion yuan (about 1.87 billion
US dollars) to build China's largest fertilizer production base in
the Yangpu Economic Development Zone on the northwest tip of
Hainan island and about 140 km from the capital of Haikou.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project will start in the latter half of
this year and is expected to be completed by 2001.
</P>
<P>
Three other major investment projects involving paper pulp,
glass and grain processing, with a combined investment exceeding
24.5 billion yuan, have also chosen Yangpu for their site and will
soon start construction.
</P>
<P>
Discussion on eight similar large projects, including an oil
refinery, polyethylene plant, and automobile assembly plant has
entered substantial stage, according to an official of the
development zone.
</P>
<P>
Yangpu, located in northwest Hainan, China's youngest province,
and facing the Beibu Gulf, was approved to be an economic
development zone by the State Council in 1992. It covers an area
of 31 sq km, 27.353 sq km of which was set aside for foreign
investment for 70 years in a package.
</P>
<P>
The developers, headed by Kumagai Gumi (Hong Kong) Limited,
have planned to invest 18 billion Hong Kong dollars in basic
construction within 15 years and build the area into an
export-oriented industrial port city with a population of 400,000
and 60 billion yuan worth of industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Since overall construction started in March 1993, 5.3 billion
yuan have been put into basic construction. Among the major
facilities which have been completed are a 315,500-kw power plant,
a supporting oil wharf and electricity grid, infrastructural
facilities in the central district, and a modernized posts and
telecommunications project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
