<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Tells Yeltsin to be Tough on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma (the lower
house of parliament) today sent a letter to President Boris
Yeltsin demanding he take a hard line with U.S. President Bill
Clinton on NATO's eastward expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
The letter won support from 268 of the 450 representatives of
of the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
The letter said NATO's eastward expansion will change the
present European geo-political situation, damaging European
security and interests, and create a new division in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The representatives asked Yeltsin to safeguard the principles
of mutual respect, equal rights, and a pan-European security
system in his Helsinki talk with Clinton scheduled next week.
</P>
<P>
They also demanded Yeltsin safeguard and consolidate Russia's
stand in talks over reductions in strategic weapons.
</P>
<P>
This is the second document the State Duma has passed this week
to express its objection to NATO expansion. The first document was
issued Tuesday, which stressed that Russia and NATO should observe
all agreements regulating bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
