<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Violence Forces Thousands of Families to Flee Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 180,000
people, mainly women and children, fled their homes in Colombia
last year because of violence.
</P>
<P>
Threats, assassinations, disappearances, attacks and torture,
often directed against men, were the main reasons forcing families
to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Human Rights and Displaced Persons office
said the problem affected 36,202 households last year, and said four
households were displaced by violence every hour.
</P>
<P>
Paramilitary forces were responsible for causing one third of
the displacements, while guerrilla groups forced 29 percent of the
displacements.
</P>
<P>
The report also says that 27 percent of the families forced to
flee came from poor areas in the capital Bogota and neighboring
districts.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the report estimates 900,000 people have been
displaced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
