<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Ships Call at Lumut Base in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lumut (Malaysia), March 15 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese naval ships
under the command of Vice Admiral Yang Yushu, commander of the
East China Sea Fleet of the Chinese PLA Navy, arrived at the Lumut
port here today for a three-day friendly visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that Chinese naval ships have visited
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"We come for friendship, we come for promoting mutual
understanding and exchanges and we come for strengthening the
friendly relations between the two armed forces and especially
between the two navies," Commander Yang said in a written
statement upon his arrival.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that this visit would surely further
enhance the continuous development of the friendly relations
between the two peoples, two armed forces and two navies of China
and Malaysia and open a new page in the history of contacts
between the two navies.
</P>
<P>
Lumut, located in Malaysia's northwestern state of Perak, about
288 kilometers from Kuala Lumpur, is the largest naval base in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese naval ships were welcomed at the base by the
assistant chief of staff of the Royal Malaysian Navy (RMN) and
other senior RMN officers.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ships came here after visiting Sattahib, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the visit in Malaysia, Commander Yang and commanding
officers of the two ships -- missile destroyer Qingdao and missile
frigate Tongling -- will meet the Malaysian fleet operations
commander, Rear Admiral Mohd Hussain Bin Tamby and RMN chief Ahmad
Ramli Mohamed Noor.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sailors will also have football and basket ball
matches with their Malaysian counterparts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
