<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexicans Furious at Drug Censure by U.S. House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Mexican politicians and
leaders united today to strongly condemn a vote by the U.S. House
of Representatives censuring Mexico's anti-drug efforts, calling
the vote unacceptable and damaging to U.S.-Mexican relations.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government rejected the decision as an
"unacceptable" attempt to interfere in its internal affairs which
would hurt bilateral drug cooperation and only benefit drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House of Representatives voted on Thursday to censure
Mexico over its anti-drug efforts. The resolution could led to the
overturning of President Bill Clinton's "certification" of Mexico
as an ally in the fight against drugs, unless Clinton reports
within 90 days that Mexico has made substantial progress in
improving its anti-drugs performance.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton certified Mexico as an ally on February 28 in
his annual review which grants or withholds certification to many
countries based on their cooperation with the U.S. in the fight
against drugs.
</P>
<P>
Jose Murat, the president of the Mexican Senate Foreign
Relations Commission, said the U.S. resolution violates
international legal principles, and demanded respect for Mexico's
national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Murat, a senator from Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary
Party (PRI), said actions of that kind only erode the healthy,
fruitful and respectful bilateral relations between the two
governments.
</P>
<P>
Augusto Gomez, president of the Foreign Relations Commission of
the Chamber of Deputies, said Mexicans are facing a stampede of
the most reactionary forces in the United States, who want to take
advantage of the situation to promote xenophobia against Mexico
and Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Mexican government to defend its sovereignty
and urge the United Nations and the Organization of American
States to declare themselves against attitudes that offend the
sovereignty and self-determination of other nations.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator of the deputies of the Democratic Revolutionary
Party, Pedro Etienne, said his party rejects and condemns the
intervention of the U.S. Congress in Mexico's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He called on Mexican legislators take a decisive stand to
defend the national sovereignty during the Mexico-United States
Interparliamentarian Meeting scheduled for April 22.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the President of the Government Commission of the
Federal District Representatives Assembly, Manuel Jimenez, said it
is unfair that the war on drugs in Mexico should be conditioned to
a 90-day deadline, since fighting this scourge is a matter that
only Mexicans should decide.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Fernandez, the general secretary of Popular Socialist
Party, said the U.S. government does not have the moral authority
to certify the work of other countries in their fight against
drugs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House's resolution must still clear the Senate before
becoming law and even then could face a presidential veto. U.S
President Bill Clinton criticized the vote, saying it was " the
wrong way to protect the interests of the American people."
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright called the vote "unwise
and self-defeating," saying it would diminish the chance of making
more progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
