<HEADLINE> Tirana Calm After Government Appeal for Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The gunfire which has echoed
around the capital Tirana was muted this evening after police and
military reinforcements appeared on the streets and a dusk to dawn
curfew was imposed.
</P>
<P>
About four to five armored vehicles carrying heavily-armed men
patrolled the main streets of the city, checking private cars,
especially those without license plates.
</P>
<P>
The usual crowds of shoppers have disappeared as shops in the
capital have all closed. Only a few people were out, running up
and down the main streets, giving out leaflets to journalists and
anyone else they could find.
</P>
<P>
Some of the leaflets read, "We should unite in the hard
times. Our children should not be without a motherland."
</P>
<P>
An emergency curfew has been imposed, forbidding people to go
out onto the streets from 19:00 to 07:00.
</P>
<P>
This morning, the Albanian national reconciliation government
ordered all soldiers and policemen to return to their units and be
ready to defend the country.
</P>
<P>
The new government, set up on Wednesday, appealed to the whole
nation in a TV broadcast for calm and ordered all active and
retired servicemen and policemen to report immediately to their
units and undertake the "holy mission of defending the motherland."
</P>
<P>
The appeal said that the country "is in danger."
</P>
<P>
Albania has been thrown into chaos and anarchy after nationwide
protests which started in January turned violent two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Rebels who seized weapons from military depots started fighting
in the south of the country. But the battles have spread to the
north and into the capital.
</P>
<P>
Seven people have reportedly been killed and dozens wounded in
the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Tanks were sent in Thursday to guard the entrances to the
country's main institutions and President Sali Berisha and the
government have called for foreign military intervention to halt
the disorder. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
