<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Forests Decrease Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's forests are now
disappearing at a rate of 100,000 hectares annually, a figure
which is tipped to rise as the nation's population and development
activities continue to increase, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesians must improve their awareness of the utilization of
natural resources which have been destroyed by uncontrolled
industrial and agricultural activities, State Minister of the
Environment Sarwono Kusumaatmadja said in Bandung, West Java, at a
meeting of farmers held on Thursday, reports reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that although some of Indonesia's unique
biodiverse areas have been destroyed, the actual level of
devastated land classified as "critical" has remained stable.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that at the beginning of the Third
Five-Year Development Plan in 1981, the area of critical land
reached 11,073,300 hectares while in 1986 it was reduced to
10,415,000 hectares. In 1991, there were 13,188,200 hectares of
critical land and in 1996 the level was down to 11,003,317
hectares.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, forest fires in the country are on the rise,
especially in Java, and they have been blamed on public
negligence.
</P>
<P>
Reports said some 10,399 hectares of forests were destroyed by
fire between January and November last year, of which 5,500
hectares were in Central and East Java.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's forests covering 144 million hectares, or about
74.6 percent of its 193 million hectares of land, were recently
declared the earth's biggest and remaining functional "lung"
(apart from those in the Amazon of Brazil).
</P>
<P>
The country has been utilizing its forest resources on a full
scale in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
At present, forests-related exports have become the country's
third largest source of foreign exchange after oil and gas and
textiles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
