<HEADLINE> Indonesia Urges Firms to Invest Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
urged big businesses in the country to invest overseas to build
and strengthen networks to penetrate foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Investing abroad would automatically create export
opportunities for Indonesia, Minister of Industry and Trade Tungky
Ariwibowo said Friday at an Indonesian-Moroccan business forum
here, according to official sources today.
</P>
<P>
The minister cited Morocco as an example of a possible
investment place which could be used by Indonesian businesses as a
springboard to the increasingly-closed European market.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has accorded Morocco's products, with 60
percent local content, duty-free entrance into its market.
</P>
<P>
"If we invest in Morocco, it means we open up opportunities to
enter Europe duty-free," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, State Minister of Investment Sanyoto Sastrowardoyo
suggested that Indonesia form a board to coordinate local
businesses investing overseas.
</P>
<P>
Some local businessmen also supported the government's
proposal, saying big businesses should pioneer foreign investment
to help medium-sized and small companies penetrate export market.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
