<HEADLINE> Albania Calls for Help From Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim
Fino has called on the European Union (EU) to provide military as
well as humanitarian assistance to Albania to restore order in the
Balkan country which is on the verge of civil war.
</P>
<P>
Fino made the appeal during a meeting with an envoy from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe on Friday,
national TV reported.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the EU should send troops to Albania as soon as
possible to help seize looted weapons and end the chaos in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the EU to provide food to the Balkan country
because stock in national stores had been looted, Fino added.
</P>
<P>
The envoy, who expressed his support for the new interim
Albanian government sworn in on Wednesday, said that the agreement
reached by all political parties in the country is the first step
toward the ending of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund will
soon send missions to Albania to sign economic accords.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha put forward similar ideas to
the EU's fledgling military arm, the Western European Union, on
Wednesday, asking for help "to restore constitutional order and
maintain the country's integrity."
</P>
<P>
Berisha also called for the setting up of reconciliation
committees nationwide to cooperate with local governments and ease
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been in the grip of unrest since January after the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
The protests turned violent two weeks ago as rebels looted
weapons from army depots and started fighting the
military. Several cities in southern Albania are in the hands of
rebels and the violence has moved north to the capital Tirana from
where hundreds of foreigners have been evacuated by the U.S.,
Italian and German military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
