<HEADLINE> Dini Reports on Albanian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Italy intends to pursue a political
settlement of the crisis in Albania and restore peace and respect
for democratic principles in the country, Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini said in a report to the cabinet today.
</P>
<P>
Dini covered developments in Albania and Italy's involvement in
trying to solve the crisis through the United Nations, the
European Union, the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE), NATO and the Western European Union, a communique
issued by the premier's office said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Italy is working at both the
political and diplomatic levels, and logistically to help the
ongoing OSCE mission led by former Austrian Chancellor Franz
Vranitzky.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to establish a lasting OSCE presence in the country,
backing dialogue between political parties and insurgents, finding
effective and secure ways for weapons to be surrendered and
ensuring human rights are respected.
</P>
<P>
Dini also reported a message of thanks from his European
colleagues for Italy's support in the evacuation of their fellow
nationals from Albania.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministry has confirmed that 900 people, including
200 Italians left the Albanian port of Durras on board two Italian
navy ships, and arrived in the Italian port Brindisi on Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Italian navy helicopters also airlifted 94 people, including 50
Italians, from Tirana on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
A dozen or so small groups of Italians still remain in Albania
and will be evacuated at their own request, the ministry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
