<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipinos Warned of Volcano Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine volcanologists have
warned residents in Legazpi, Albay Province, against entering a
six-kilometer-radius danger zone around the Mayon Volcano which
has become active with increased crater glow and sulfur emissions
during the past few days.
</P>
<P>
In a report to Albay's disaster coordination council Friday, Ed
Laguert, resident volcanologist of the Philippine Institute of
Volcanology and Seismology, said the unstable condition of Mayon
has prompted the institute to raise its status to Alert 1,
signifying possible magnetic disturbance.
</P>
<P>
Observatory records showed continuous crater glow of the
volcano since January 20, he said.
</P>
<P>
Laguert said the seismic sensor at the Mayon Rest House Station
in Tabaco, Albay, detected 22 relatively high-level local
earthquakes on February 28.
</P>
<P>
He said sulfur dioxide emissions have also increased from the
background level of less than 200 tons to around 1,000 tons a day.
</P>
<P>
Volcanologists' recommendation prohibits entry into the
six-kilometer permanent danger zone until a decline in the
activity of Mayon.
</P>
<P>
At least 78 people were killed when the volcano erupted on
February 2, 1993.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
