<HEADLINE> Swedish Athletics Association Gets Financial Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Swedish Athletics
Association has been saved from bankruptcy with a 11.3 million
Swedish crowns (1.5 million U.S. dollars) financial aid from the
the Swedish government, it was announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sports minister Leif Blomberg told a press conference the money
was to cover the loss from the 1995 World championships in
Gothenburg.
</P>
<P>
Blonberg said a number of unsatisfactory deals were made for
the Gothenburg championships, "but this does not in any way affect
the government's views on the possible Olympics in Stockholm in
2004."
</P>
<P>
The government has guaranteed the Stockholm Olympics
organisation 2.5 billion crowns (333 million U.S. dollars) if they
are awarded the games.
</P>
<P>
The Athletics Association made a total loss on the Gothenburg
championships of around 25 million crowns (2 million U.S. dollars)
on a turnover of five billion crowns (666 million U.S. dollars),
and AA chairman Bengt Westerberg said on Friday that "the help
from the government will keep the largest creditors off our backs
and save us from bankruptcy."
</P>
<P>
Westerberg, also chairman of Telia (Swedish Telecom) who are
owed a large sum from the championships, said he hoped the city of
Gothenburg would help fund the rest of the deficit. 
</P>
