<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marriage Status of Shanghai People Changing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey in China's
largest city of Shanghai shows that people's idea of marriage is
undergoing big changes, as more couples are tying the knot at a
younger age, and divorce is becoming more common.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of single people above age 25 -- the standard
age for marriage according to an international marriage survey --
is on a general decline in the city, while the divorce rate is
rising, especially among young people, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
In China, the legal age for marriage is 22 for both men and
women.
</P>
<P>
Among the people between the ages of 22-29, about one-third of
the women are single, and more than half of the men.
</P>
<P>
Men account for 84 percent of the unmarried in the 30-49 age
group, five times the number of single women, according to the
survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that among older single people, women
have higher education and better jobs than men.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that in Shanghai, one out of every 100 people
above 25 is divorced. In 1995, the total number of divorced people
reached 45,300, up 40 percent over the figure of 1990.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this indicates that Shanghai citizens have paid
greater attention to the quality of marriage in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the number of people who have remarried since 1990
stands at about 20,000 per year -- more than the figures in the
1980s, but still far lower than the number of people divorced each
year.
</P>
<P>
The survey concluded that the major obstacles for remarrying
are connected with difficulties involving property, housing and
children, as well as the traditional negative attitude toward
remarriage among older people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
