<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Tombstone Museum Given State Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China's only museum for ancient
tombstones, in Xinan county in central China's Henan Province, has
been listed among museums under state protection.
</P>
<P>
The museum consists of caves and courtyards and has more than
1,400 tombstones dating from the Western Jin Dynasty to modern
times.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,200 are from the Tang Dynasty (618-907), and record
lives of people from all walks of life, from royal family members,
literati, and monks to ordinary people. It is for this reason that
the museum has been called "Qian Tang Zhi Zai" (Hall of a Thousand
Records of the Tang Dynasty).
</P>
<P>
Chinese scholars say they value the stones for their
inscriptions, most of which were written by famous calligraphers,
such as Chu Suiliang, Yan Zhenqin, and Liu Gongquan -- all top
calligraphers from the Tang Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The museum was set up by Zhang Fang, a general who collected
tombstones discarded by tomb robbers in the 1920s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
