<HEADLINE> Sino-Foreign Co-operation Spurs Beijing's Electronics Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Cooperative projects launched
between domestic electronics manufacturers and some big
international firms are becoming a new growth impetus for the
industry in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of the gross output and 80 percent of the
sales volume in Beijing's electronics sector have been achieved so
far by joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one trans-national electronics firms, including such big
names as ABB, Philips, Matsushita and Mitsubishi, have invested an
aggregate 600 million US dollars to open 89 joint ventures in the
city, which plans to develop the electronics sector into its No. 1
pillar industry.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale technological cooperation and the introduction of
advanced technology and equipment have encouraged the enterprises
to frequently update their products, such as optical fiber cables,
video recorders, personal computers, and household electric
appliances.
</P>
<P>
The industry expects its annual turnover to reach 55 billion
yuan (6.6 billion US dollars) by the year 2000, which will account
for nearly 14 percent of the nation's total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wenzhou Urban Cooperative Bank To Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Wenzhou, one of the first
Chinese cities to adopt market-led reforms, has been given the
go-ahead from the People's Bank of China to establish its urban
cooperative bank.
</P>
<P>
It will be the city's first public-held, local commercial bank,
according to local official sources.
</P>
<P>
Wenzhou is known for its booming private firms, which so far
number 40,000 and account for over 90 percent of the city's total
industrial production.
</P>
<P>
The new bank, Wenzhou Urban Cooperative, will be formed on the
basis of 29 local urban credit agencies. It will operate under one
legal person, with the state to hold 30 percent of the stock,
former credit agencies to share 50-60 percent, and other legal
person units to buy 20-30 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, the first credit agency was set up in the city and by
the end of last year, there were 48, with deposits amounting to
over five billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local banking experts speak highly of the role of these credit
agencies in supporting the city's private sector, but note that an
urban cooperative bank should be set up to overcome the weak
points of these agencies, such as poor management.
</P>
<P>
The proposed urban cooperative bank is expected to be formally
established by October, according to the sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
