<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin: Helsinki Talks May be Hardest Yet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said today that his summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton next
week would be the hardest talks since he became Russian president
in 1991 and the "hardest in the history of Russian-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin did not exclude the possibility of a fruitless ending
to the talks, saying that "we will not make any compromise that
may weaken Russia's defense ability."
</P>
<P>
This is the Russian government's stand.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia will never agree to let Americans deploy
conventional weapons on the territories of eastern European
countries, formerly members of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Moscow, Yeltsin said he would also
insist that in no way should the Baltic and countries of the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) be admitted as members of
NATO.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin expressed his concern over a series of contacts NATO's
Secretary-General Javier Solana has made with leaders of CIS
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president said that he resolutely opposed the idea
of changing Russia's negative stance on NATO expansion as a trade
off for receiving investment from the U.S.. The U.S. government
had promised to invest about four billion dollars in Russia if it
cooperated in NATO's eastward expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
