<HEADLINE> China Rules Roost as Champions Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- All England Championships'
singles finals -- men and women -- will both be all-Chinese
affairs for the first time in the event's history when Olympic
gold medallist Poul-Erik Hoyer-Larsen and world champion Heryanto
Arbi were both beaten in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
The two men, who have each won the All England title twice,
both fell to Chinese players.
</P>
<P>
Joint ninth seed Dong Jiong carried out a sweet revenge of
15-8, 15-10 win over Denmark's Hoyer-Larsen, the man who had
beaten him in Atlanta to take the Olympic title.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's Arbi also lost in straight sets, 15-10, 15-11, to
former world junior champion Sun Jun, seeded joint three.
</P>
<P>
On Friday Sun produced his fourth win in succession over Arbi,
who slipped down the rankings following injury and has been back
in full training for only three months.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles, world champion Ye Zhaoying beat
Chinese compatriot Dai Yun 11-1, 5-11, 11-2, while Gong Zhichao
swept past South Korea's Ra Kyung-min 11-3, 11-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
