<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Shifts More State Assets to Service Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- China's leading economic center
of Shanghai has redistributed its state assets in key industries,
to facilitate its ambition to evolve into an international
metropolis.
</P>
<P>
More assets are directed to the service sector, which accounted
for 51.4 percent of the city's 95-billion-yuan state property at
the end of 1995, compared to two percent in the agricultural
sector and 46.6 percent in industry.
</P>
<P>
The insurance industry proved to be a rising star in the
service sector; its output value accounted for 24.8 percent of the
service industry in 1995, up from 20.6 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The adjustment of industrial structure also gave full play to
science and technology, which now adds 36 percent to Shanghai's
economic growth, up from 26 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the nationwide strategy of "encouraging large
state-owned enterprise groups and granting small state ventures
more management flexibility," 57 large state enterprise groups
have been formed in Shanghai to improve the quality of the assets.
</P>
<P>
"The redistribution of the state assets in the three industries
well serves the city's globalization goal, and also gives a real
boost to the state sector in Shanghai," said a local official with
the Administrative Office of State Assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch Against Olympic Professionalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, March 14 (Xinhua) -- President Juan Antonio Samaranch
said on Friday that he opposed paying athletes to participate at
the Olympics and expressed doubts over the effectiveness of
pre-competition doping tests, just introduced into cycling.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch made clear he still believed in the Games' amateur
vocation as he decried the IAAF's decision to award event winners
and those setting new world records 50,000 U.S. dlllars a time at
last week's world indoor athletics championships in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"If the athletics world thinks that paying athletes money is a
good means of promoting the sport then that is their business,"
Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
But athletes in contrast participate in the Olympics "because
it is an honour to take part in the world's most important
sporting occasion," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
On the question of pre-race haemoglobin tests for drugtaking,
recently introduced by the International Cycling Union (UCI),
Samaranch told reporters he believed it was "too early to apply"
such a measure.
</P>
<P>
"The UCI, which is no stranger to the doping problem, deserves
our praise for taking this measure, but I hope it does not run
into legal problems in applying it", he said.
</P>
<P>
The tests are designed to deter the use of EPO, or
erythropoietin, a drug produced to treat kidney disease and used
to increase oxygen-carrying red blood cell levels which improve
endurance.
</P>
<P>
They were introduced at the request of riders at the end of
January as part of the fight against the use of EPO in the sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
