<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former World Champions Left out of Russia Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Former world pairs champions
Yevgenia Shishkova and Vadim Naumov have been dropped from the
Russian team for the world figure skating championships next week
in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
The Russian figure skating federation said the decision
followed the couple's poor perfomance at the European
championships in Paris last month.
</P>
<P>
They are replaced by former world and Olympic champion Artur
Dmitriev and his new partner Oksana Kazakova.
</P>
<P>
Dmitriev won world, Olympic and European gold in the early
1990s with Natalia Mishkutienok. He made a successful comeback
with Kazakova to win the European title last year and they placed
fifth in the world championships in Edmonton, Canada.
</P>
<P>
World champions Oksana Gritshchuk and Yevgeny Platov are on top
form to defend their ice dance title.
</P>
<P>
Olympic and European gold medallist Alexei Urmanov, former
European champion Ilya Kulik and Alexei Yagudin will challenge
Canadian favourite Elvis Stojko for the men's title.
</P>
<P>
Double European champion Irina Slutskaya is the arch rival of
14-year-old Tara Lipinsky and fellow American Michelle Kwan, 16,
for the women's title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
