<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama registered a 2.5 percent economic growth
in 1996, which interrupts a negative trend accumulated in the last
few years and puts its public debt at 7.005 billion U.S. dollars,
said Planning and Economic Policies Minister Guillermo Chapman
today.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian economy, which rose to 9.4 percent in 1991, lost
vigor in 1995, when the growing index was 1.8 percent, one of the
lowest in the history of this country.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The European Union, Israel, and Brazil continue
being the main markets for Uruguayan meat exports, which grew 52
percent in the beef sector, and 23 percent in the mutton sector
during the two first months of 1997, compared to the same period
last year, according to the National Meats Institute.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina industrial output will grow 6 percent
this year, four percentage points more than in 1994, when it
reached its highest record in the last 28 years, according to
official data published today.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production forecasts for 1997 is expected to surpass
by 12 percent as compared with that in 1995, when there was a
recession caused by the Mexican financial crisis reverberations,
said a report from the Industry Ministry.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- A great trade center with 18 buildings will be
built in the Miramar section of the Cuban capital, announced
S.A. real state company.
</P>
<P>
By the completion of the project, the complex will have a total
area of approximately 180,000 square meters, which will house
offices, commercial establishments, restaurants, travel agencies
and banks.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean forest products exports will reach this
year 1.970 billion dollars, a 6.5 percent increase over the 1.85
billon dollars earned in 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to Fernando Leniz, Chilean Lumber Corporation
president, the total sale of forest products abroad made up
11.8 percent of the total hard currency received by the country in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Leniz said wood pulp will lead the sales of the forest sector
and will obtain 830 million dollars, a 2.5 percent increase over
1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
