<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Wins Sullivan Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Michael Johnson, who became
the first man to claim the golds at 200 and 400 meters at the
Atlanta Olymics Games last year, has won the Sullivan Award as
1996's most outstanding United States sports amateur.
</P>
<P>
Johnson will be presented the trophy as the 67th winner on
Monday. Johnson, a three-time finalist for the award, became the
37th athlete to be honoured.
</P>
<P>
Johnson won the 200m in a world record 19.32 seconds and swept
the same double he had claimed at the world championships.
</P>
<P>
The award honoured outstanding performances of 1996. No prior
winner is eligible again for consideration among a panel of 1,000
voters conducted by the Amateur Athletic Union.
</P>
<P>
Other finalists were Gail Devers and Dan O'Brien from
athletics, skater Michelle Kwan, basketball player Teresa Edwards,
gymnast Shannon Miller, softball pitcher Dot Richardson, swimmer
Amy Van Dyken, American football player Danny Wuerffel and golfer
Tiger Woods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
