<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan unemployment rate continued at a
high level during the November-January quarter, although it
registered a slight drop in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in Montevideo was 11.6 percent in the
period, dropping 0.1 percent as compared with that in the
October-December quarter.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate reached 12.2 percent in the urban
interior, against 11.6 percent registered in the last quarter of
1996.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- National fuels consumption registered a
small increase in 1996, compared to previous years.
</P>
<P>
The daily demand of regular gasoline stabilized at an average
of 117,000 barrels, a 0.4 percent reduction in consumption, while
gasoline extra showed a 6.4 percent increase, equivalent to 11,500
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
A daily consuming of 56,000 barrels of diesel showed an
increase of 7 percent in demand.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- After the announcement made by the United States
government this week about the increase to the sugar quota for
1997, Nicaragua will be able to export more sugar to that country,
raising it from 34.076 million metric tons to 38.34 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The report released by the Nicaraguan Foreign Relations
Ministry says that this new quota allocation, 4.264 million tons
more, is a record for the export of Nicaraguan sugar to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Investments from entities not residing in
Argentine reached 16.94 billion U.S. dollars in January this year,
45 percent more compared to the same month of 1996, said the
National Stock Market Commission.
</P>
<P>
This group increased its investments 0.8 percent compared to
December of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The countries with the biggest participation in investments in
Argentina are the United States, the United Kingdom, and Begium.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The rate of poverty in the Panamanian population
dropped to 30 percent in 1996, compared to 45 percent registered
in 1990, announced Guillermo Chapman, Planning and Economic
Policies Minister.
</P>
<P>
This figure is still too high. People who receive a minimum
salary cannot acquire the basic staples basket, which costs 225
dollars.
</P>
<P>
People in this situation of extreme poverty are a fifth of the
total population.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Telephone companies will invest 550 million
pesos (approximately 72 millioin dollars) in public telephone in
the next three years, the Mexican Association of Public Telephone
Operators said today.
</P>
<P>
The investments of 23 firms supplying public telephone services
will permit a 47 percent increase in the number of public
telephones, which reached 231,142 telephone booths in September of
1996.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian 1997 grain harvest could reach a
little more than 81.185 million tons, as announced by Brazilian
Agriculture Minister Arlindo Porto.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the grain production during this year is due to
the recovery of the south of the country with more rain and
increased sale of fertilizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Puts Forward Anti-Racism Proposal in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese delegation today put
forward a three-point proposal for a more strenuous UN fight
against new forms of racism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ongoing 53rd session of the UN Commission on
Human Rights in Geneva, Alternate Representative of the Chinese
delegation Xie Bohua made the following proposals:
</P>
<P>
1. The United Nations should continue to condemn and give
priority attention to all forms of racism and racial
discrimination, particularly new forms of racism which are all
gross violations of human rights.
</P>
<P>
In the activities planned for the Third Decade to Combat Racism
and Racial Discrimination, the fight against new forms of racism
should be given a prominent place.
</P>
<P>
The work of the Committee on the Elimination of Racial
Discrimination should be vigorously supported.
</P>
<P>
2. The UN's relevant bodies should be mobilized to conduct a
comprehensive study of contemporary forms of racism with a view to
an in-depth analysis of its social causes and its various
manifestations and to recommend effective measures, in order to
obtain the aim of "the speedy and comprehensive elimination of all
forms of racism and racial discrimination, xenophobia and related
intolerance" as set forth in the Vienna Declaration and Program of
Action.
</P>
<P>
3. Countries still plagued by these phenomena should face up to
their responsibility and take all necessary measures to realize
genuine equality, human rights and fundamental freedoms for their
people, regardless of their racial or ethnic origins.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government has been steadfast in its stand against
racism and racial discrimination," Xie pointed out. "China highly
appreciates and supports the UN Decade to Combat Racism and Racial
Discrimination and its follow-up activities."
</P>
<P>
"In the future, China will continue to enhance its cooperation
with other members of the international community in the
relentless struggle to once and for all eliminate racism from our
planet," Xie said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SLeonean Riot Police Prevent Students Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Heavily armed riot police
sealed all fields in the capital today to present university
students from holding a meeting to discuss what they claimed as
''national issues''.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time in three days that the police have taken
such action.
</P>
<P>
A government statement broadcast on state radio said the
police have been ordered ''to take appropriate but reasonable
action to prevent a student group meeting anywhere throughout
Sierra Leone''.
</P>
<P>
''Any violators will be prosecuted whether they are students
or not,'' the statement warned.
</P>
<P>
The statement urged students ''not to be used as pawns by ill
motivated groups to disrupt the peace and good order in the
nation''.
</P>
<P>
It said students can hold their meetings at any of the
campuses throughout the country but not in any area outside the
university.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said they were surprised at the tough stand
taken by the government on the issue when both sides had come
''relatively closer'' following a meeting on tuesday after police
had dispersed the students with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the University Students Union NUSS
Mucturr Bomtay said, ''the government has back-tracked from a
previous commitment to allow the meeting to go ahead.''
</P>
<P>
Many Sierra Leoneans have not supported the students stand
amid increasing insecurity as a result of the rebel war and a
poor economic performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
