<HEADLINE> German Car Output Sees Another Drop in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- German automotive production plunged
sharply in February after a 1-percent drop in January, the
Frankfurt-based German Automobile Industry Association (VDA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Germany produced a total of 406,400 vehicles in February, down
7 percent from February 1996. Of the total, 378,900 were passenger
cars and vans, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The VDA blamed the shrunk output partly on the delivery
problems induced by the truck drivers' strikes in Spain.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that while domestic demand for private cars
remained weak in February, foreign demand remained robust. After a
9 percent increase in January, foreign orders rose a further 5
percent in February.
</P>
<P>
A total of 248,200 vehicles were exported by Germany in
February, and 230,600 of them were passenger cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
