<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Still Expects Agreement With S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Government has not
lost hope of reaching a bilateral trade agreement with its
southern neighbor South Africa, Industry and Commerce Minister
Nathan Shamuyarira said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists in Mutare of east Zimbabwe, the
minister said his country would welcome any negotiations which
would result in a mutually beneficial trade agreement with South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
While attending the London Investment Conference last week,
the minister was reported as having been pessimistic about
negotiations with South Africa, saying he would only believe in
any agreement when it was implemented.
</P>
<P>
But today the minister said there were plans to resume
meetings with South Africa. One between him and his South African
counterpart Trevor Manuel was scheduled for April 1, this year.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''we are going to talk to South Africa and at this
moment we cannot say the government has lost hope on reaching
some agreement. We are still talking.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Decides to Go Ahead With Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli cabinet today
decided to begin carrying out the controversial building project
in Har Homa in East Jerusalem next week.
</P>
<P>
In the six-hour weekly meeting, all ministers voiced their
backing to go ahead with the Har Homa project despite the
increasing pressure from the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
and the international community.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet instructed the Housing Ministry to
present a plan within a week on housing construction for Arab
residents in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan which was approved two weeks ago by the
Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs, Israel would build
6,500 Jewish housing units in Har Homa, while at the same time
building 3,000 units for Arab residents in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Today's cabinet meeting was held just after the United
Nations General Assembly overwhelmingly passed a resolution
calling on Israel to drop the Har Homa project.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat has time and again condemned the
Har Homa project, warning that such action could lead to renewed
violence. He has called an international meeting of foreign
diplomats in Gaza Saturday to muster more international support.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the Israeli cabinet decided to carry out the
project on the assumption that Israel's compromise would only
lead to more outside pressure.
</P>
<P>
The crisis between Israel and the PNA was also intensively
discussed at today's cabinet session, which reviewed the whole
security situation and possible Palestinian reaction to Har Homa
construction. Ministers heard briefings from Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai and other senior officials from the security
establishment.
</P>
<P>
Security officials warned the cabinet that PNA President
Yasser Arafat appeared to be easing his crackdown on the
extremist militant groups Hamas and Islamic Jihad, a move that
could lead to renewed violence. Both Hamas and Jihad have been
launching attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was held in the wake of the tragic shooting
incident Thursday on the Israeli-Jordanian border, in
which a Jordanian soldier shot dead seven Israeli teenage
schoolgirls and wounded six others. The meeting begun with a
moment of silence for the victims.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed the request by Jordanian King Hussein
to pay a private visit to Israel to offer his personal
condolences to the families of the victims. It is expected that
Hussein would travel next week to Beit Shemesh, west of
Jerusalem, to visit the bereaved families.
</P>
<P>
Hussein is eager to mend the ties with Israel following the
Thursday shooting which has set back the already soured bilateral
relations due to the Israeli-Palestinian tension.
</P>
<P>
Israel blamed the shooting incident on Hussein's recent
harsh criticism of Netanyahu over his hardline policies on Har
Homa and further troop pullbacks in the rural West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
