<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   British Envoy: Chances for Cyprus Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- British envoy for Cyprus Sir
David Hannay expressed his belief today that chances for a Cyprus
settlement are better now, and face-to-face talks between the two
communities on the island should begin before the end of the
coming June.
</P>
<P>
The British envoy made the remarks at a press conference at the
Ledra Palace Hotel in U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia prior
to his departure for Brussels after a three-day visit here.
</P>
<P>
He described his two separate meetings with President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, as well as a
lunch with party leaders from both sides of the divide, as
"extremely useful."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the British government's view that face-to-face
negotiations between President Clerides and Denktash should take
place before the end of the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, he said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will convene
such a meeting on advices from his representatives and after
consulting others who are active in working out a settlement in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Sir David did not go into specifics about the issues discussed
during his visit.
</P>
<P>
The envoy spoke of the problems of reaching a solution, which
have met repeated failures in the past, but he believed "the
chances of getting a settlement are better than they have been for
quite a long time in the past."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his satisfaction with the fact that the two sides
"are getting a little bit away from general statements and into
identification of things that are really important to each side
as that is the basis for negotiation."
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, Sir David will brief Annan's Special
Representative for Cyprus, Han Sung Joo, and European Union
External Affairs commissioner, Hans van den Broek, on his talks in
Cyprus and his recent contacts in Ankara and Athens.
</P>
<P>
Sir David's visit here is part of international community's
peace effort to bring about an early solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored proximity talks between the two communities
on the island started Monday, which were aimed at paving the way for
face-to-face negotiations between President Clerides and
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
The two men have not met since October 1994 when two rounds
of informal talks between the two leaders were held under the
U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of a
short-lived coup seeking union with Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
