<HEADLINE> Greece Ready to Receive Refugees From Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Greece is preparing to receive
refugees from Albania in line with a request from the United
Nations High Commission for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
This was announced today by the government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas today.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said, however, the question had not been raised of
offering asylum to Albanian President Sali Berisha whose
whereabouts were reportedly unknown.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said no communication had yet been received
regarding talks currently under way between Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) special envoy Franz
Vranitzky and Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yannos Kranidiotis with
representatives of the Albanian government and the insurgents.
</P>
<P>
The talks are being held on an Italian frigate off the coast of
the Albanian port of Durres.
</P>
<P>
Reppas noted that no representatives of the U.S., Russian or
Italian governments are participating in the talks.
</P>
<P>
With regard to an eventual multinational force for Albania, the
spokesman said that Greece would only participate if an official
request in writing were made on behalf of all political forces in
Albania, with a specific legal framework, under the auspices and
control of an international organization. Nevertheless, he
emphasized that there was no such plan to date. 
</P>
