<HEADLINE> US Lawmakers Oppose US Participation in Gaza Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen Republican members of
Congress have accused President Bill Clinton of participating in a
Gaza meeting on the Middle East peace process organized by
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers, including House speaker Newt Gingrich, said in a
letter, dated March 13 and released today, that U.S.
representation at the meeting Saturday was "a critical mistake and
a slap in the face of a faithful ally."
</P>
<P>
"By agreeing to participate in the Gaza conference, the United
States is sending the message that it is possible to drive a wedge
between the United States and Israel," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has said he is convening the meeting, which is also to
be attended by European, Arab and Asian countries, to salvage the
peace process after a series of Israeli actions which have
seriously strained relations with the Palestinians and threatened
the future of negotiation.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has recently decided to build Jewish
homes in historically Arab east Jerusalem, to shut down four
Palestinians offices in the holy city and to cede only 9 percent
of the rural areas in the West Bank in the first of three stages
of withdrawal, far short of requirement from the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly of the United Nations Thursday censured
Israel's decision of house construction in east Jerusalem by
overwhelmingly adopting a critical resolution, similar to the one
vetoed by the United States last week in the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, disagreeing to the U.N. resolution,
however, has criticized Israel rhetorically over the Israeli
housing plan, and accepted an invitation from Arafat to attend the
Gaza meeting.
</P>
<P>
In explaining the reason of U.S. attendance, State Department
spokesman Nicholas Burns said it was to give the Palestinians "an
opportunity to express their concerns about the present situation
in the Middle East and to hear views of friendly countries like
the United States."
</P>
<P>
But he said the United States "does not see this meeting as
forum for decisions on the Middle east peace issues or as a
negotiating session." 
</P>
</TEXT>
