<HEADLINE> Veteran Liberian Politican Tipoteh Joins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A veteran Liberian politician,
Togba-Nah Tipoteh, on Thursday announced his intention to contest in
the country's May 30 presidential elections, a report reaching here
said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally of the Liberia People's Party (LPP) at the
Monrovial City Hall, Tipoteh said that if Liberians are looking
for a president free of corruption, immortality and capable of
managing the economy and building institutions, he is the one.
</P>
<P>
The LPP is one of the seven politicial parties that have formed an
alliance to contest the presidential and parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
"Let the alliance take due note that Tipoteh is the presidential
candidate the alliance needs, and with Tipoteh, the alliance will win
the May 30 elections," said Tipoteh, the LPP Chairman.
</P>
<P>
Tipoteh was the Minister of Planning and Economic Affairs
under the regime of former President Samuel Doe, who was
assassinated in 1990, months after the Liberian civil war broke
out.
</P>
<P>
A former professor of economics at the University of Liberia,
Tipoteh now heads Liberia's oldest aid agency, the Susuku, which gives
scholarships and other incentives to more than 10,000 ex-combatants to
encourage them to disarm.
</P>
<P>
The alliance will decide who will represent it at the elections
during its convention next week, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates for the presidency include Charles Taylor,
who ignited the Liberian civil war in December 1989, and George
Boley, the leader of the Liberia Peace Council.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Kromah, who heads the United Liberiation Movement, also
announced his intention to run for the presidency and is widely
regarded as one of the strongest candidate.
</P>
<P>
But the hope for him now dims as he is facing prosecution after
peace-keepers found large quantities of weapons in his homes in
Monrovia recently.  
</P>
</TEXT>
