<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Employment Growth in City of London Raises Concerns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Employment in international
financial services in London is set to grow by up to 2.5 percent a
year over the next 25 years, with up to 60,000 new jobs coming in
the next decade, mainly in the City.
</P>
<P>
The forecast, released here today, is from a study commissioned
by the Corporation of London, the local authority for the Square
Mile.
</P>
<P>
The study looks at the growth prospects of the City's
industries over the next 20-25 years and the implications for
employment growth and office space needs.
</P>
<P>
Sectors analyzed include domestic banking, international
banking, forex, securities trading, derivatives trading, corporate
finance, insurance, accountancy and law.
</P>
<P>
Employment growth rates are translated into office demand based
on assumptions on office occupancy rates, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
Calculations for the minimum scenario result in a projected
requirement of 10-15 million sq ft of office space in the Square
Mile over the next 10 years and an additional 5-10 million sq ft
for the five years after that.
</P>
<P>
The growth scenarios raise many questions over the location of
such activity in London and consequent implications for public
services, transport infrastructure and labor requirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
