<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Helicopter Comes Under Fire in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- One of the six German helicopters on
the evacuation mission came under fire today in Albania, Inspector
General Hartmut Bagger of the German armed forces said in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
The helicopter returned fire, he said. No one on board was
injured.
</P>
<P>
The flight was part of the first such operation the German
armed forces, known as Bundeswehr, have ever taken in the post-war
era.
</P>
<P>
Despite the incident, the six CH-53 helicopters deployed with
the SFOR (Stabilization Force) multinational peacekeeping forces
in Bosnia had managed to ferry about 120 people out of Tirana,
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel and Defense Minister Volker
Ruhe told a news conference later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said 20 Germans, including 11 embassy staff, about 100
people of 15 other nationalities, including 12 Austrians, 11 Swiss
as well as Japanese, Danes and Hungarians, had been evacuated.
</P>
<P>
Describing the operation as "extremely dangerous," Ruhe said
the German helicopters, all heavily armed, originally planned to
land in front of the U.S. embassy in Tirana, but another landing
site was used after a U.S. gunship came under fire near the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
The evacuees would be first taken to Montenegro of the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia, from where they would be flown by Transall
supply aircraft to Bonn in the evening, the ministers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
