<HEADLINE> Closed Canadian Embassy to Nigeria Still Partly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Canada announced on Wednesday the temporary closure of the high
commission for security concerns. Its acting high commissioner and
other officials have returned home as the closure took effect on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the embassy said that locally-engaged consular
staff would be available to provide limited services under the
supervision of the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The statement said "all Canadian visa applications and
documentation for permanent residence" should be sent directly to the
Canadian High Commission in Accra, Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Although Canadian passport applications would continue to be
processed in Lagos, the passports would be issuded in Accra, the
Ghanaian capital.
</P>
<P>
All applications for a visitor visa, student and employment
authorization or returning resident permit could be made in person at
any Canadian high commission or embassy, including those in Accra and
Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Canada and Nigeria have been sour since November
1995 when the Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership as an answer
to its execution of nine minority nationality activists.
</P>
<P>
Canada has been insisting on further sanctions against Nigeria,
which closed down its High Commission in Canada last September due to
financial reasons.  
</P>
