<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Vows to Keep Currency Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will not revaluate its
currency at present, Egyptian Central Bank Deputy Governor Faeqa
al-Refaee announced today.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Egyptian pound will be subject to supply and
demand, she told a symposium on Efficiency and Modernization in
Economic Information in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria,
235 kilometers northwest of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
She said the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has asked Egypt, in
the light of the successful economic performance it has made, to
revaluate the Egyptian pound.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the IMF had urged Egypt to devaluate the pound as a
precondition for supporting Egypt's economic reform program,
Refaee added.
</P>
<P>
The bank official pointed out that Egypt's balance of payments
scored, for the first time, a surplus of 600 million dollars in
the later half of 1996. "This means that the Egyptian economic
policy has succeeded," she said.
</P>
<P>
Refaee said the Egyptian Central Bank's foreign currency
reserves have dropped by about 100 million dollars to 18.9 billion
dollars after the bank met its debt commitments to the Paris Club
members and domestic commodity requirements.
</P>
<P>
However, according to an IMF official, the IMF is now pressing
the Egyptian government to further implement structural reforms so
that the value of the pound will fluctuate in line with the market
situation.
</P>
<P>
IMF chief Arvind Subramanian said there is a large rise of
capital inflows in Egypt behind the market pressure to prop up the
exchange rate, however the Egyptian government is resisting the
pressure and doest not want the pound to appreciate and
consequently affect the export sector.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank official dismissed reports that the government
have immediate plans to privatize public sector banks.
</P>
<P>
"Only after the completion of the privatization of joint banks,
due to be finalized by the end of this year, could the government
consider putting up other banks for sale," she added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief has said recently that the government is fully
committed to privatizing the banking sector, especially keen to
quickly eliminate government holdings in joint-venture
banks.
</P>
<P>
At the current inflation rate, Refaee said that Egypt's
financial policy is aimed at bringing down inflation to less than
7 percent by July from January's 7.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has embarked on the economic reform program since 1982 but it
only quickened the pace in 1991 when free currency exchange,
reduction of subsidies, adjustment to prices and further
liberalization of export were introduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe/Mozambique Joint Commission Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The two-day Eighth Session of the
Joint Commission of Zimbabwe and Mozambique concluded here
today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries at the end of the session signed a joint
commission agreement which will pave way for the suspension of
visas for diplomatic passport holders.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Zimbabwean Foreign Minister
Stan Mudenge said the agreement, which he signed with his
Mozambican counterpart Leonardo Simao, would lead to a cultural
agreement between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe welcomed the progress made towards the
conclusion of an extradition treaty between Zimbabwe and
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
He said Zimbabwe also welcomed the much-awaited preferential
trade agreement between the two countries scheduled to be
concluded within the next three months.
</P>
<P>
He added that the joint commission had requested major
universities in Zimbabwe and Mozambique to develop reciprocal
language training programs so as to enhance communication and
exchange of information between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to launch joint operations to
control locusts and tsetse flies along their common borders.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said, ''our efforts over the last few days have also given
a major boost to our cooperation in the fight against trans-border
crime, in particular, commercial and customs fraud as well as drug
trafficking.'' enditem

