<HEADLINE> Tories Revive Aggressive Attack on Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The British Tories today
reactivated an aggressive propaganda battle against the opposition
Labor Party, warning that Labor was duping voters with promises to
cut taxes and hold spending in check.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Party's central council meeting for encouraging
the Party's confidence in Bath, western England, Chancellor
Kenneth Clarke said: under Labor, Britain could turn its back on
the liberalizing economic approach.
</P>
<P>
"If you vote Labor, you call a halt to tax-cutting, you vote
for higher spending, you give more powers to the trade
unions...voting Labor means an end to the economic reform agenda
which has transformed Britain from basket-case to role model," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Michael Portillo launched a direct attack on
Labor leader Tony Blair, saying "Tony Blair or John Major?
Slippery Tony or Honest John. That is the choice: not only a
choice of men but a choice of parties and principles."
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the Conservative strategists are using "one
simple proposition" to voters during the general election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The aim is to contrast what they call Major's track record of
"stability in an uncertain world" with the "risk of a leap in the
dark by a man who would do anything to get elected"
</P>
<P>
However, the efforts by senior Tories to rally the party for a
drive to win the fifth term to Downing Street were shadowed by
some Tory MPs indulging in public speculation about what would
happen if they lost.
</P>
<P>
Former minister Edwina Currie told BBC that manoeuvring ahead
of a post-election leadership contest was already under way.
"There is already a great deal of formation of columns and lines
and factions and groups," she said.
</P>
<P>
Currie even called on Prime Minister Major to resign quickly as
party leader if the Tories were to lose, saying "Please, John,
please don't make us hang around. Please don't make us wait...."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Currie's remarks, a BBC correspondent said her
remarks could not be worse timed, with a likely election on May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
