<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. Watching Albanian Situation Closely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States is closely
watching the situation in Albania, fearing that violence would
spread to neighboring countries in the Balkans, U.S. Defense
Secretary William Cohen said today.
</P>
<P>
"This seems to be an isolated case as far as Albania is
concerned, but obviously it could have spill-over effects," Cohen
told reporters in a Pentagon briefing.
</P>
<P>
"If you have a mass flow of refugees trying to move into other
countries that could cause some instability so all of the
countries in that region are concerned about bringing order to
what is clearly a state of anarchy right now," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that at the moment, the U.S. was trying to get
Americans out of Albania. "We're watching it very closely," Cohen
said. "Our sole motivation right now and goal and objective is to
get the Americans out of there safely."
</P>
<P>
Cohen added, "Beyond that there is no planning for U.S.
intervention."
</P>
<P>
Marine Corps Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, director of operations for
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told reporters at the Pentagon that 170
Marines are in Tirana, capital of Albania, and nearly 2,000 more
are available off shore if needed.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Marine Corps have been evacuating American diplomats and
other Americans in the country in the last couple of days. But
helicopters suspended evacuation operations today after taking
ground fire in two incidents.
</P>
<P>
The Marines came ashore from three amphibious ships that also
carrying nearly 2,000 sailors that routinely patrol the
Mediterranean as part of the U.S. forward-deployed force in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the United States has about 500 troops in
neighboring Macedonia and nearly 8,000 in nearby Bosnia as part of
peacekeeping operations in the Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
