<HEADLINE> European Shares Up on Benign US Economic Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- All the three major stock markets
in Europe opened lower Friday, but later reversed the trend and
ended in positive ground, as benign US economic figures eased
fears of a near-term US interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
British shares in London recovered much of their early losses
after US producer price data showed a greater fall than expected,
easing interest rate rise fears.
</P>
<P>
A strong opening on Wall street today also lifted the London
market higher, with the FTSE 100 index ending up 26.6 points at
4,424.3, once again above the 4,400-point level, and a gain of
four points over last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt market in Germany, which suffered the heaviest
losses on Thursday, also staged a recovery later today, boosted by
the US economic data, although trading volumes were modest, with
the DAX-30 shares closing 9.48 points higher at 3,359.29, a loss
of 60.22 points on last week.
</P>
<P>
On the Paris bourse, French shares recovered from early losses
on the back of Wall Street's renewed strength. Firmer French bond
prices also helped to fortify stocks, with the CAC-40 index
closing the week 13.52 points higher at 2,645.62, but 62.66 points
down from a week ago.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index of leading British shares ended 26.6
points higher at 4,424.3. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index finished up
9.48 points at 3,359.29. In Paris, the CAC-40 index closed 13.52
points stronger at 2,645.62.  
</P>
