<HEADLINE> Uganda-Sudan Talks Open in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The talks between Uganda and
Sudan were officially opened by Ugandan President Y. Museveni in
Murchison Falls National Park, western Uganda, today, reported
Radio Uganda.
</P>
<P>
In his opening remarks, Museveni expressed hope that the talks
would find solutions to the problems between the governments of
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He, however, urged the concerned parties to discuss the issue
of southern Sudan, noting that the problems between the two
countries stem from the issue.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern about the terrorist methods used by the
Sudanese government in unleashing the rebel criminals of the
Lord's Resistance Army to propel the war in northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
He emphasised that the government of Uganda does not suppport
the war in southern Sudan but sympathises with the struggle of
the southern Sudanese people to guard their god-given rights and
emancipate themselves.
</P>
<P>
Museveni explained that the peoples of Africa will be mutually
linked together through promotion of trade and investment,
infrastructure development, peace and respect of equality of all
peoples in an appropriate constitutional framework.
</P>
<P>
He therefore called for serious, thorough and fruitful
deliberations which can harmonise the relations between the two
countries and help to curtail the activities of Sudanese-
sponsored terrorists who mutilate Ugandan civilians and kidnap
school children.
</P>
<P>
