<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Production Increases 0.5 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua)-- The production at the U.S.
factories, mines and utilities increased by 0.5 percent in
February, the strongest in three months, the U.S. Federal Reserve
(Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Fed also revised the industrial production in January down
to a decline of 0.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that manufacturing output rose 0.8 percent in
February after a 0.2 percent decrease in January. The gain mainly
reflected a rebound in durable goods such as appliances, business
equipment and construction supplies all registering gains.
</P>
<P>
The production of nondurable goods rose by 0.3 percent,
retracting part of the decline in January.
</P>
<P>
U.S. industries operated at 83.3 percent of capacity, up from
83.2 percent in January. Those are levels that allow room for
production increases without inflationary bottlenecks developing.
</P>
<P>
The factory operating rate rose by 0.4 percentage point to 82.5
percent in last month, slightly above the level of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In another sign of a pressure-free economy, the U.S. Commerce
Department reported today that business inventories edged 0.1
percent higher in January after an identical decline in December.
</P>
<P>
An unwanted buildup of inventories can cause layoffs and
production cutbacks as businesses try to clear warehouses and
backlogs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
