<HEADLINE> World Bank to Offer 121 Million U.S. Dollars to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will offer 121
million U.S. Dollars for the infrastratural reconstruction of the
five war-damaged cities of Angola -- Huambo, Kuito, Luena,
Uige and Menongue.
</P>
<P>
Ana Dias, a senior official in Angola's Ministry for Planning,
said in the central city of Huambo today that the money will be
used in restoring schools, hospitals, some streets and the water
and electricity supplies in the cities.
</P>
<P>
Huambo, the largest city in Angola, will get more than 17
million Dollars from the World Bank, six million of them for
buying hospital equipment and more than 7.6 million for
restoring schools and buildings.
</P>
<P>
The city will spend the rest of the money on improving its
roads and water and electricity supplies.
</P>
<P>
Now, the World Bank is working with the cities' authorities on
the final drafting of the restoration plan, according to a report
by the Angolan News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan civil war broke out again in late 1992, causing
serious damage to the five cities, especially Huambo and Kuito.
