<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Appeal WTO Magazine Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government said today
that it is preparing to appeal the recent World Trade Organization
(WTO) ruling against its policy of blocking so-called "split-run"
magazines.
</P>
<P>
The WTO made public its ruling on the case today, by
circulating the final report to all WTO members. The report
supports three of four complaints made by the United States to the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
The trade case was filed by the U.S. at the WTO in March 1996
after a long battle over the attempts of the U.S. Time Warner Inc.
to establish an edition of Sports Illustrated magazine in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The magazine was forced to shut down its three-year old
Canadian edition after Canada began to impose the 80 percent tax
in December 1995 on the revenue of split-run magazines.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. complained that the new tax violates "national
treatment" provisions in the 1995 WTO pact.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO, a government must treat foreign companies the
same way they treat domestic ones.
</P>
<P>
Canada insisted that the tax was acceptable because of a WTO
clause that it did not sign, and was a reasonable response to a
U.S. attempt to raid the limited Canadian advertising market.
</P>
<P>
On June 19, 1996, the WTO set up a dispute-settlement panel to
address the U.S. complaint covering four Canadian measures related
to magazines.
</P>
<P>
The measures include Canada's Tariff Code 9958 that prohibits
the import of split-run magazines, the 80 percent excise tax on
advertising in split-run magazines, the postal subsidy and the
commercial publications mail rates that favor Canadian magazines.
</P>
<P>
Of these four disputed measures, the WTO has upheld Canada's
right to maintain a postal subsidy for Canadian magazines.
</P>
<P>
Under the WTO, both parties to the dispute may appeal legal
aspects of the decision. The WTO Dispute Settlement Understanding
allows a maximum of 60 days for the parties to file their appeal.
</P>
<P>
"The trade law experts are examining very thoroughly the
details of the ruling," Canadian minister for International Trade
Art Eggleton said while announcing the appeal decision today.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government is working together with the Canadian
magazine industry "to plan our appeal strategy and to assess the
full impact of this ruling on the industry," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The final report states very clearly that this decision does
not take issue with the ability of any WTO member to take measures
to protect its cultural identity," noted Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Canadian Heritage Sheila Copps.
</P>
<P>
"Canada will continue to promote its cultural objectives and
ensure that Canadians have access to magazines that speak to us
about our own country," she said.
</P>
<P>
Both Eggleton and Copps also stressed the WTO decision does not
immediately change the rules of business for Canadian magazines.
</P>
<P>
"The laws, policies and programs of Canada remain as they are
unless Canada decides otherwise," Eggleton said.
</P>
<P>
Despite Canada's plan to appeal the WTO ruling, the chance of
any major change in the final ruling would be quite remote,
analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling has dealt a serious blow to the Canada's efforts to
protect its already endangered magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that half the English-language magazines in
Canada and four-fifths of those sold in newsstands are at present
from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Carefully Monitoring Albanian Situation </HEADLINE>
