<HEADLINE> King Hussein Postpones Trip to Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan has
postponed his scheduled trip to Washington next week for talks
with President Bill Clinton, the White House announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Partly because of King Hussein's schedule and partly now
because of the president's schedule, both the Jordanian side and
the U.S. side felt it was better to postpone King Hussein's
scheduled visit here to Washington on Monday," White House
spokesman Michael McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Reports has already come out that King Hussein might put off
his visit to Washington when a Jordanian soldier shot dead seven
Israeli school children on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein cut short a visit to Spain on the same day and
returned to Jordan. He expressed condolences to Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and said he had asked to meet with the
families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has also had to change his schedule as he was
undergoing surgery at a hospital for an knee injury incurred early
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein is the last of four Middle East leaders who were
scheduled to meet Clinton in Washington for discussions on the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was the first to come at the end of February, and
his visit was followed by Palestinian President yasser Arafat
and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
