<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Promises No Permanent Stationing of Conventional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- NATO made today another attempt
to allay Russia's concerns about its expansion plan by promising
that there will be no permanent stationing of conventional troops
on the territory of new members it plans to admit from Central and
Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
This step followed a meeting of the North Atlantic Council,
NATO's decision-making body, chaired by NATO Secretary General
Javier Solana, at NATO Headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
An "Unilateral Statement" issued by the North Atlantic Council
said: "In the current and foreseeable security environment, the
Alliance will carry out its collective defense and other missions
by ensuring the necessary interoperability, integration and
capability for reinforcement rather than by additional permanent
stationing of substantial combat forces."
</P>
<P>
However, the statement stopped short of a guarantee that NATO
will not deploy Western troops in its new members under any
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
It also did not mention moving eastward the Alliance's military
infrastructure, such as military communications, air defenses and
fuel pipelines, a step which is firmly opposed by Russia.
</P>
<P>
In last December, NATO has assured Russia that it has "no
intention, no plan, and no reason" to deploy nuclear weapons on
the territory of new members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rebounded Friday
amid new signs that inflation has remained tame despite worrisome
indications a day earlier that led to a 160-point tumble by the
Dow industrials.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 56.57 points to
6,935.46, taking back about a third of Thursday's slide which was
the fifth biggest after July 15.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 486.93
million shares, down from 503.73 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 3.61 to 793.17, the
NYSE's composite index rose 1.83 to 417.70, and the American Stock
Exchange composite index rose 2.45 to 600.47.
</P>
<P>
But the Nasdaq composite index gave back some gains by the
close, falling 0.29 to 1,292.99.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported this morning that wholesale
prices paid to farms and factories fell by 0.4 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected decline more or less calmed down investors'
worries about rising inflation and a possible interest rate hike
by the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The new data helped bonds rebound. As bond prices rose today,
the yield on the 30-year Treasury fell as low as 6.91 percent from
late Thursday's 6.96 percent before settling at about 6.94
percent.
</P>
<P>
Helping fuel the Dow's rise today was a partial rebound by
Philip Morris. On Thursday, the cigarette and food maker plunged
more than 10 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
