<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Passes Resolution on Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will
suspend its activities in Tajikistan, except for a limited
presence of the U.N. Mission of Observers, due to the
deterioration in security.
</P>
<P>
According to a resolution passed here this afternoon by the
U.N. Security Council, the decision was made by the
Secretary-General Kofi Annan after the personnel of the United
Nations, the peace keeping forces and other international
personnel in Tajikistan were attacked continuously in the country.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also says the Security Council decides to extend
the mandate of the U.N. Mission of Observers in Tajikistan (UNMOT)
until June 15, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The resolution "strongly condemns" the acts of mistreatment
against UNMOT and other international personnel, and urgently
calls upon the parties to cooperate in bringing the perpetrators
to justice, to ensure the safety of the international personnel.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also calls upon the government of Tajikistan to
take further and more rigorous measures to this end, thus enabling
the international community to support Tajikistan on its difficult
path "from armed conflict to normal peaceful life."
</P>
<P>
The resolution also says that the Security Council welcomes
the results of the latest round of inter-Tajik talks held in
Moscow from February 26 to March 8, including the agreements on
disarmament and disbandment of the armed units of the United
Tajik Opposition, reforming the power structures of the Republic
of Tajikistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
