<DOCNO> XIE19970315.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Appoints Humanitarian Coordinator for Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Under-Secretary-
General for Humanitarian Affairs and Emergency Relief Coordinator,
Yasushi Akashi, announced on Friday the appointment of Pierce
Gerety as Regional Humanitarian Coordinator for the Great Lakes
Region.
</P>
<P>
Gerety, a United States national, will succeed Martin
Griffiths, who has resumed his functions as Director of the Geneva
Office of the Department of Humanitarian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Gerety has most recently served as Great Lakes Region Emergency
Coordinator for the United Nations Children's Fund. He has also
acted as Coordinator and UNICEF Chief of Operations for Operation
Lifeline Sudan and as UNICEF Representative in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told the press that
Rwandan Hutu refugees were dying in Zaire's jungles and drowning
while crossing rivers, and its expressed alarm athe their plight
as the rainy season begins.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 hungry and exhausted refugees have arrived at
the town of Ubundu on the Zaire River unstream from the eastern
town of Kisangani after a long trek across the rainforest, fleeing
advances by mainly Tutsi rebels fighting Zairean troops.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said 200 to 300 refugees drowned in a heavy storm in
crossing the Zaire River in small boats on Thursday. One makeshift
raft carring 76 people was washed away and reports indicated the
Rwandan refugees were paying as much as two U.S. dollars a person
to cross.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
